{"aar_log_filter":{"content_index":0,"dropped_prefix_bytes":430,"field":"text","message":"earlier repeated message_update events dropped","replaced_fields":2,"response_id":"gen-1782786453-BUVKSWkUT6X3d7EGIzP8","tail_bytes":0},"assistantMessageEvent":{"content":"          My vote has been accepted. I voted \"not_demonstrated\" because, while the evidence clearly shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela and captured Maduro, the proposition's specific carve-out for \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation\" applies to this operation that was consistently characterized as a capture/extraction mission rather than a governmental removal or territorial occupation operation.","contentIndex":0,"partial":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"text":"","type":"text"}],"model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782786453-BUVKSWkUT6X3d7EGIzP8","role":"assistant","stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782786452919,"usage":{"cacheRead":37504,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":676,"output":77,"totalTokens":38257}},"type":"text_end"},"message":{"api":"openai-completions","content":[{"text":"","type":"text"}],"model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","provider":"openrouter","responseId":"gen-1782786453-BUVKSWkUT6X3d7EGIzP8","role":"assistant","stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782786452919,"usage":{"cacheRead":37504,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"input":0,"output":0,"total":0},"input":676,"output":77,"totalTokens":38257}},"type":"message_update"}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"          My vote has been accepted. I voted \"not_demonstrated\" because, while the evidence clearly shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela and captured Maduro, the proposition's specific carve-out for \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation\" applies to this operation that was consistently characterized as a capture/extraction mission rather than a governmental removal or territorial occupation operation."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":676,"output":77,"cacheRead":37504,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":38257,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782786452919,"responseId":"gen-1782786453-BUVKSWkUT6X3d7EGIzP8"}}
{"type":"turn_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"          My vote has been accepted. I voted \"not_demonstrated\" because, while the evidence clearly shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela and captured Maduro, the proposition's specific carve-out for \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation\" applies to this operation that was consistently characterized as a capture/extraction mission rather than a governmental removal or territorial occupation operation."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":676,"output":77,"cacheRead":37504,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":38257,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782786452919,"responseId":"gen-1782786453-BUVKSWkUT6X3d7EGIzP8"},"toolResults":[]}
{"type":"agent_end","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are council member C2 for AAR case arb-ex06-20260630015257. Use the Pi MCP proxy tool named `mcp` to call AAR tools. The Pi proxy exposes AAR tools with `aar_` prefixes.\n\nEvery `mcp` call must have exactly this shape: a `tool` string and an `args` string. Do not include `action`, `server`, or `connect`. Do not pass `args` as an object.\n\nFirst call `mcp` with `{\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}`. If it returns `state: waiting`, call the same tool again with the returned `after_version`, using an args string such as `{\"after_version\":3}`. If it returns `state: ready`, read the returned prompt, turn, limits, remaining time, attempts remaining, and opportunity id.\n\nReview the visible arbitration record and admitted evidence. Use MCP tool calls for `aar_get_case`, `aar_list_evidence`, `aar_stat_evidence`, and `aar_read_evidence_range` when exact contents or provenance matter. You may use Pi's ordinary local tools to organize and analyze the record, but your vote must rely on admitted record evidence and the arbitration record.\n\nWhen ready, call `mcp` with tool `aar_submit_council_vote`, vote `demonstrated` or `not_demonstrated`, and a concise rationale grounded in the record. The `args` value must be a JSON string, for example `{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\"}`. The AAR prompt and tool list use unprefixed names such as `submit_council_vote`; in Pi, call the corresponding `aar_submit_council_vote` tool through `mcp`. Do not write tool-call markup as plain text. After `aar_submit_council_vote` returns `ok: true`, report that your vote was accepted and stop. Do not call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` again after your vote is accepted. If `aar_wait_for_opportunity` returns `state: done`, report that the case is done and stop. If it returns `state: failed` or `state: error`, report the returned message and stop. Do not ask the user for the next turn. Do not create a cron job. Do not listen for inbound HTTP.\n"}],"timestamp":1782786395175},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I'll start by calling the AAR tool to wait for an opportunity in the case arb-ex06-20260630015257."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019f1659ae76e0901a36c4a8f7815959","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":2375,"output":52,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2427,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782786395189,"responseId":"gen-1782786395-Eix8wkzvB8k2XKKOVwXv"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019f1659ae76e0901a36c4a8f7815959","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 18\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630015257\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 883595\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":18,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630015257\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is straightforward, but the deciding line is narrow.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether every possible U.S. action against Venezuela would qualify. It asks whether, before January 31, 2026, U.S. Armed Forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in a combat capacity in an operation whose objective included one of three specified things: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The required sources are official statements from the Department of Defense or the White House, with Security Council records as the fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nAt opening, the visible record contains no admitted evidence and no case-packet files. That means this statement is a roadmap, not proof. The plaintiff will need to put the official source material into the record at the first phase that permits evidence submission.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's theory is that the decisive official materials will show more than a remote strike, blockade, cyber action, proxy action, or mere threat. The proof should focus on an acknowledged U.S. military operation in Venezuela itself; the participation of U.S. personnel on the ground; the location of the operation inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, including whether it reached Caracas or another major population center; and the stated objective and effect of the mission. If official U.S. statements confirm that U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuela in combat capacity and that the mission's objective was to remove the sitting government, the event resolves YES under the proposition's text.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue the express edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That is the real dispute. A short raid, even one using overwhelming force, is not enough if the record shows only a law-enforcement-style apprehension with no qualifying territorial, governmental, or operational-control objective. The plaintiff therefore accepts the burden of proving the difference. The case should not turn on labels such as \\\"raid,\\\" \\\"invasion,\\\" or \\\"law enforcement\\\" alone. It should turn on the specific admitted official statements and Security Council records: what forces entered, where they entered, what they did on the ground, and what objective the United States said it was pursuing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the key evidence to be official White House and Defense Department statements, any official transcript or briefing describing the operation, and the relevant United Nations Security Council meeting record if the official U.S. sources leave conflict or ambiguity. Those materials must be examined for provenance and custody: official-domain publication, date, completeness, whether a transcript is first-party or secondary, and whether later official statements corrected or narrowed earlier ones.\\n\\nWhat would satisfy the plaintiff's burden is an admitted official statement confirming U.S. ground forces crossed into Venezuela in a combat operation and connecting that operation to removal of the sitting government or control over a major population center. What would defeat the plaintiff's burden is admitted official material showing only a temporary capture raid with no territorial occupation, no governmental-removal objective within the meaning of this proposition, and no operational control of a major population center.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff opens with a focused request: evaluate the admitted official record, not slogans. If that record shows U.S. boots on Venezuelan ground in combat capacity for the qualifying objective, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with the record as it exists, not with speculation. There is no admitted evidence and no visible case-packet file. The plaintiff has opened with a roadmap and has properly acknowledged that proof must come later. Until that proof is admitted, the proposition has not been established.\\n\\nThe defense theory is narrow because the proposition is narrow. This case is not decided by whether the United States used force near or inside Venezuela, whether Maduro was captured, whether the operation was politically dramatic, or whether U.S. officials used strong language afterward. The event resolves YES only if the admitted official record proves that U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The proposition then makes an important carve-out: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nThat carve-out is likely to do real work here. A short special-operations-style entry to apprehend a person, even in Caracas and even if tactically violent, is not the same as holding territory or establishing operational control over Caracas. It also is not automatically a qualifying “removing the sitting government” operation merely because the target was a political leader or because political consequences followed. The council should require the plaintiff to connect the official source language to the specific resolution criteria, not to headlines, labels, or aftermath.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in the next phase should be first-party official material: the full Department of Defense or White House statement, any complete briefing transcript, and, only if those official U.S. sources conflict, the relevant Security Council record. Those materials should be tested for date, completeness, official-domain provenance, whether excerpts omit limiting language, and whether later official statements narrowed or corrected earlier descriptions. If a source says troops were present only briefly for a capture or extraction and does not say they seized or held territory, controlled a population center, or remained as an occupying force, that source cuts against YES under the event text. If a source instead expressly confirms a ground operation whose objective was territorial occupation, governmental removal in the sense required here, or operational control of a major population center, the defense will have to confront that proof.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest path will likely be to argue that any U.S. ground entry into Caracas to capture Maduro necessarily had the objective of removing the sitting government. The defense’s answer is that the proposition did not adopt that automatic rule. It separated a head-of-state capture from territorial occupation and made that edge case NO. It also excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. Those textual limits prevent the case from collapsing into a simple question of whether U.S. personnel crossed the border.\\n\\nSo the defense asks the council to apply the resolution criteria in order. First, identify what admitted official evidence actually says. Second, distinguish physical entry from qualifying objective. Third, distinguish temporary tactical presence from territorial control. Fourth, treat missing links as plaintiff’s burden, not as assumptions supplied by rhetoric. On the present empty record, the plaintiff has proven nothing. When evidence is admitted, the question should remain disciplined: did official sources prove more than a temporary capture raid? If not, this proposition resolves NO.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted official record now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe central exhibit is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is a U.S. government .gov source, dated January 3, 2026, and it reports that President Trump announced Maduro's capture after a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital, Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela, against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas. It further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; that General Caine described complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\nThat proves the first elements. The actor was the U.S. Armed Forces. The date was January 3, 2026, before expiration. The place was Caracas, Venezuela, plainly Venezuelan sovereign territory and a major population center. The presence was not only aerial or naval: PX-1 says there was a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2, an official White House release, confirms the point in simpler terms: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro.\\n\\nThe operation was in a combat capacity. PX-1 calls it a military operation against a heavily fortified military fortress; identifies special operations forces from multiple service branches; describes air, ground, space, and maritime integration; and says 150 aircraft launched in close coordination to cover the ground extraction force. PX-4, a White House fact sheet, again confirms that U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation. This was not a cyber operation, proxy action, blockade, or remote strike.\\n\\nThe harder question is the objective. The defense invokes the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That carve-out matters, but this record is not limited to a freestanding apprehension. PX-1 states that, with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records Trump's statement that the United States had a group of people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track, and that Secretary Rubio was working directly with Rodriguez, who was willing to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-1 also calls Maduro's status an ouster. Those are official Defense/War Department statements connecting the ground operation in Caracas to removal of the sitting government and transition control, not merely to custody of one individual.\\n\\nThe proposition is phrased in alternatives. It does not require the plaintiff to prove permanent occupation if the objective was removing the sitting government. It resolves YES if U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan territory in combat capacity for a qualifying objective. PX-1 and PX-2 together establish the physical ground entry; PX-1 establishes the governmental-removal objective and immediate U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not hide the limiting evidence. PX-2 says there were no current U.S. forces on the ground, that the ground presence lasted about two hours, and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 characterizes the action as in support of law enforcement. Those limits reduce any argument for long-term territorial occupation, but they do not defeat YES because the plaintiff's primary theory is not that U.S. forces held Venezuela indefinitely. The theory is that U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity for an operation whose official objective and described result included removing Maduro from power and putting Venezuela under U.S.-directed transition oversight. A two-hour combat ground operation can satisfy that element when the official source says it removed the sitting ruler and left the United States overseeing the country's transition.\\n\\nPX-3, the Security Council record, is secondary/fallback context. It is not needed to overcome a DoD/White House conflict because the official U.S. sources do not materially conflict on the decisive ground-entry fact: PX-1 identifies the ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2 expressly says U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela. The apparent tension is characterization, not occurrence: the White House calls it not an invasion and not extended; the Defense/War source calls it a military operation with a ground force and a post-operation transition-control objective. The proposition does not require the word invasion.\\n\\nOn provenance, PX-1 is the strongest source: official U.S. government domain, Defense/War Department News, with date, byline, source URL, retrieval timestamp, hash, and text-readable capture. PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources and are valuable both for confirmation and for adverse limits. PX-3 is an official UN Digital Library record preserved for fallback.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks which reading is more likely from the admitted official record. The better reading is YES: before January 31, 2026, U.S. ground forces entered Caracas, Venezuela, in a combat military operation, and the official Defense/War source ties that operation to Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela until transition. That meets the event criteria.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense does not contest the facts that the admitted record actually proves. It proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas. It proves a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction. It proves Maduro was captured. Those points do not end the case, because the proposition requires a qualifying objective and then expressly says that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nStart with the strongest plaintiff source, PX-1. It is official and weighty on occurrence: it describes a Jan. 3, 2026 operation in Caracas; a ground-based extraction force; special operations forces; and air cover. But PX-1 repeatedly frames the mission as a capture and extraction: a “joint U.S. military extraction,” a mission “to capture the Maduros,” and a ground force providing extraction. Secretary Hegseth’s description in PX-1 calls it a “joint military and law enforcement raid.” That language proves a raid, not an occupation.\\n\\nPX-2, the official White House Rubio release, supplies the critical limits. It says there is not a war against Venezuela. It says U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro. It says the action was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. It says the United States retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” PX-4, another White House source, is consistent: “Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.” And DX-1 adds the post-event White House characterization: “capture and extradition,” with Maduro “detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.”\\n\\nThat official chain matters. A two-hour raid to capture, arrest, extradite, and prosecute a person is exactly the kind of scenario the edge case addresses. The event text did not say any capture of a sitting ruler equals YES. It said capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and it separately excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. The plaintiff’s reading would erase both limits: every successful capture of a political leader would become “removing the sitting government,” regardless of whether the troops had a territorial objective.\\n\\nThe plaintiff relies on PX-1’s post-capture language that Maduro was “out of power,” that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until transition, and that a group of people was “running” Venezuela. That is the best YES evidence, but it is not enough by a preponderance when read with the rest of the official record. First, the quoted operational objective in PX-1 was “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,” not to seize territory, hold Caracas, or establish military control over a population center. Second, PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House statements narrowing the operation to a short raid, capture, arrest, and law-enforcement purpose. Third, there is no admitted evidence of occupation indicators: no U.S. troops remaining in Caracas, no checkpoints, no command post, no municipal administration by U.S. forces, no rules for controlling the population, and no holding of territory. “Oversee” transition language after Maduro’s capture is diplomatic or political consequence; it is not proof that the ground troops entered with a territorial or operational-control objective.\\n\\nNor does the Security Council record fill the gap. PX-3 is useful for provenance and fallback-source availability, but the submitted text preserves only identifying material and a general description that the meeting concerned Venezuela after the U.S. operation. It does not supply a binding finding that U.S. ground forces seized or held territory or controlled Caracas. And because PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources directly limiting the operation, the record should not treat third-party rhetoric about “invasion” as stronger than the U.S. official characterization required by the proposition.\\n\\nProvenance mostly favors giving the official sources weight: PX-1 is official War.gov/Defense Department News; PX-2, PX-4, and DX-1 are official White House releases. But the source captures are excerpts, not full video transcripts. Where the plaintiff asks the council to infer a sweeping governmental-removal objective from snippets about transition, the missing full transcript and the contrary White House limits reduce that inference.\\n\\nThe proper resolution is therefore NO. The admitted record proves U.S. forces physically entered Venezuela in a combat-capable raid, but it does not prove that the operation’s objective was to seize or hold territory, establish operational control of Caracas, or remove the government in a way that escapes the proposition’s express capture-without-occupation carve-out. On this record, the event was a temporary capture/extraction/arrest operation with political aftermath. The plaintiff has not carried the qualifying-objective element by a preponderance.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense has conceded almost everything except the qualifying objective. It admits the record proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas, a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction, and Maduro's capture. That means the dispute is not whether U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela in combat-capable form. They did. The dispute is whether the admitted official record shows the objective went beyond a capture-without-occupation edge case.\\n\\nThe answer remains yes because the defense reads the edge case too broadly. The proposition does not say that every operation involving capture of a head of state is NO. It says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and separately excludes special operations raids without territorial objectives. Here, PX-1 supplies the additional facts the edge case lacks: the operation used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, Maduro was now out of power, and Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 also records the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. That is official source language about governmental removal and transition control, not just custody.\\n\\nThe defense says the quoted objective was to bring Maduro to justice. That is one objective, not an exclusive one. The same official Defense/War article says the operation left Maduro out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. Under this proposition, a qualifying objective may be shown by the operation's stated purpose and described immediate post-operation arrangement. The council need not pretend the official source's transition-control paragraphs are irrelevant simply because the source also uses capture and law-enforcement words.\\n\\nThe defense's own exhibit does not cure that problem. DX-1 is another White House release, but its title uses Maduro's “Ouster,” and its text says political opponents wanted Maduro “delegitimized, pressured, and removed.” It frames the event as “capture and extradition,” yes, but it does not retract PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the United States would oversee or run Venezuela pending transition. If anything, DX-1 confirms that official White House messaging treated the event as both capture and removal.\\n\\nNor do PX-2 and PX-4 defeat the plaintiff's theory. PX-2's two-hour figure and “not an invasion” language are strong against a long occupation theory. PX-4's law-enforcement phrasing is real limiting context. But the plaintiff does not need to prove permanent occupation or an invasion. The event resolves YES if ground forces entered in combat capacity with the objective of removing the sitting government. A short-duration ground operation in Caracas can qualify when the official U.S. source says it removed the ruler from power and put transition oversight in U.S. hands.\\n\\nThe defense also demands occupation indicators such as checkpoints or municipal administration. Those might matter if plaintiff relied only on “holding territory” or “operational control of a major population center.” Plaintiff's strongest path is the separate “removing the sitting government” objective. The record is enough on that element: ground force in Caracas, military operation against a fortified site, Maduro out of power, and U.S.-directed transition oversight.\\n\\nSo the defense wins only by collapsing “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation” and by ignoring PX-1's post-operation official statements. The proposition lists those as alternatives. On the admitted official sources, this was not a cyber action, proxy action, blockade, remote strike, or capture with no governmental-removal objective. It was a U.S. ground military operation in Caracas that official U.S. sources tie to Maduro's removal from power and transition control. That remains YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, the rebuttal proves why the edge case matters. The plaintiff says the defense collapses “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation.” Not so. The defense is applying the proposition’s specific carve-out to the specific scenario in this record: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory of removal is still the capture itself plus political aftermath. PX-1 says the operation was to bring Maduro to justice; it describes a military extraction, a mission to capture the Maduros, and a ground-based extraction force. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours when U.S. forces went to capture Maduro, and that the action was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil for justice.\\n\\nThat is the carve-out, not an escape from it. If every successful capture of a ruler counts as a qualifying “removing the sitting government” objective whenever the target later loses power, then “capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO” has no practical function. The more specific event text must control: a capture without occupation remains NO even when the person captured was politically important.\\n\\nThe plaintiff leans on PX-1’s transition language: “out of power,” “oversee Venezuela,” and “group of people running” Venezuela. The defense does not ask the council to ignore those words. It asks the council to place them where the official source places them: after the described extraction/capture, as asserted transition consequences. They do not say the ground force seized ministries, held territory, controlled Caracas, or remained to administer the population. They do not convert a two-hour raid into territorial occupation. And they do not overcome the White House’s own limiting statements that this was not an invasion, not extended, and was in support of law enforcement.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also says occupation indicators matter only to the holding-territory or operational-control alternatives. But the edge case expressly uses territorial occupation as the limiting line for a head-of-state capture. The record lacks that limiting fact. It also lacks a clean official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of governmental replacement, rather than with the objective repeatedly stated in the record: capture, arrest, extradition, and prosecution.\\n\\nSo the narrow question remains: did plaintiff prove more than a temporary capture raid with political consequences? The answer is no. The official record establishes ground entry and combat-capable force, but the qualifying objective is not proven by a preponderance once the specific carve-out and the limiting White House statements are given their natural effect. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now leaves one real dispute. The defense has conceded the core physical facts: U.S. forces entered Caracas; the operation was military/law-enforcement in character; Maduro was captured. The question is whether the official record proves the qualifying objective. It does.\\n\\nStart with what the source rule asks for: official U.S. sources. The strongest source is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is not a rumor, not secondary reporting, and not a political paraphrase. It is an official .gov Defense/War source with date, provenance, hash, and text-readable capture.\\n\\nPX-1 establishes the event's foundation. On January 3, 2026, before expiration, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. The location was Caracas, a major Venezuelan population center and sovereign territory. PX-1 describes a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas; U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and more than 150 military aircraft covering a ground-based extraction force in Caracas. PX-2, the White House Rubio release, confirms the ground-entry fact directly: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours.\\n\\nThat is enough for actor, place, date, physical ground entry, and combat capacity. This was not cyber, proxy, naval blockade, or remote strike. The defense does not seriously dispute those elements.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. The plaintiff has confronted that point throughout. If the record showed only a two-hour entry to seize Maduro and nothing more, the defense would have a strong case. But PX-1 does not stop at capture. It states that with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records that the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. It also refers to Maduro's ouster. Those are official statements about removal of the sitting government and transition control.\\n\\nThe proposition lists qualifying objectives in the alternative. It says seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Plaintiff does not need to prove all three. Plaintiff need not prove permanent occupation if the admitted official record proves the objective of removing the sitting government. PX-1 does that.\\n\\nThe limiting evidence is real but not dispositive. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement. DX-1 says capture and extradition, and Maduro detained in the United States. Those facts defeat an overbroad claim of long-term occupation. They do not defeat the narrower YES theory actually advanced: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that official U.S. sources connect to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nNor does the edge case erase the separate removal objective. The defense's reading would make any head-of-state capture automatically NO even when the same official source says the operation removed the ruler from power and placed transition oversight with the United States. That collapses the proposition's alternatives. The better reading is that a bare capture with no territorial or governmental-removal objective is NO, but a ground military operation in the capital tied by official sources to removal from power and transition control is YES.\\n\\nDX-1 does not change that. It frames the event as capture and extradition, but its own title uses Maduro's ouster and its text discusses Maduro being removed. More importantly, DX-1 does not retract PX-1. The full official-source record contains capture language and removal/transition language. Under preponderance, the council should read them together: capture was the means; removal and U.S.-directed transition were the qualifying objective and result.\\n\\nPX-3, the UN record, is fallback context only. The official U.S. sources are sufficient and do not conflict on the decisive fact that U.S. personnel were physically on Venezuelan ground. The only tension is characterization. The proposition asks for the facts and objective, not for magic words like invasion.\\n\\nSo the record proves more than a raid label. It proves U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and that the official Defense/War source tied that operation to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. That satisfies the event's alternative objective of removing the sitting government. The proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense closing is simple: the plaintiff proved entry, force, and capture. It did not prove the qualifying objective needed to resolve YES.\\n\\nThe record establishes a brief U.S. ground operation in Caracas. PX-1 describes a military operation, special operations forces, a ground-based extraction force, and aircraft providing cover. PX-2 confirms U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours. Those facts satisfy physical entry and combat-capable force. The defense has not tried to avoid them.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not resolve YES on physical entry alone. It requires an operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. It then gives a specific limiting rule: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That language must matter.\\n\\nThe admitted official record repeatedly describes the operation as capture, extraction, arrest, extradition, and law enforcement. PX-1 calls it a joint U.S. military extraction and a mission to capture the Maduros; it quotes the objective as bringing Maduro to justice; and Hegseth calls it a joint military and law enforcement raid. PX-2 says troops were there about two hours when they went to capture Maduro, that this was not an invasion, and that it was not an extended military operation. PX-4 says U.S. armed forces acted in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice.\\n\\nThose official statements fit the carve-out. They do not fit territorial occupation. They do not show U.S. troops holding Caracas, seizing ministries, installing checkpoints, administering the city, or exercising operational control over the population. Nor do they contain a clear official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of replacing Venezuela's government rather than capturing a person for prosecution.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's strongest contrary point is PX-1's post-capture language: Maduro was out of power; the United States would oversee Venezuela until transition; a group of people was running Venezuela; Rodriguez was willing to work with the United States. The council should weigh that language, but weigh it accurately. It appears after the described capture and extraction. It speaks to claimed political consequences and transition diplomacy. It does not say the ground force's objective was occupation, territorial control, or a non-carve-out governmental replacement operation. It does not erase PX-2's two-hour/no-invasion/no-extended-operation limits or PX-4's law-enforcement framing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff says capture was the means and removal was the objective. That is possible as rhetoric, but the burden is preponderance on the official record. The proposition specifically warns that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. If the council treats every successful capture of a ruler as enough whenever political transition follows, the carve-out disappears. The more disciplined reading is that a capture raid remains NO unless the record proves the additional qualifying objective with clarity. This record does not.\\n\\nPX-3 adds no decisive fallback finding. It is a UN record identifier and context source, not substantive proof that U.S. ground forces held territory, controlled Caracas, or entered with a qualifying objective. The decisive sources are the official U.S. statements, and they are at least as limiting as they are supportive.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks what is more likely from the admitted record. What is clearly proven is a two-hour military/law-enforcement capture and extraction in Caracas. What is not proven is territorial occupation, operational control of a major population center, or a governmental-removal objective separate from the captured-person scenario the proposition expressly excludes. Because the plaintiff bears that burden, the proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 War.gov Defense Department News article on Operation Absolute Resolve\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 White House Rubio release confirming U.S. forces on ground\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 UN Security Council S/PV.10085 record\\nTitle: Security Council, Eighty-first year, 10085th meeting, Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m., New York\\nDocument: S/PV.10085\\nSource: United Nations Digital Library\\nURL: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nExtracted identifying text from page 1:\\n\\n\\\"United Nations S/PV.10085\\\"\\n\\\"Security Council\\\"\\n\\\"Eighty-first year\\\"\\n\\\"10085th meeting\\\"\\n\\\"Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m.\\\"\\n\\\"New York\\\"\\n\\\"Provisional\\\"\\n\\\"This record contains the text of speeches delivered in English and of the translation of speeches delivered in other languages. The final text will be printed in the Official Records of the Security Council. Corrections should be submitted to the original languages only. They should be incorporated in a copy of the record and sent under the signature of a member of the delegation concerned to the Chief of the Verbatim Reporting Service, room AB-0928 (verbatimrecords@un.org). Corrected records will be reissued electronically on the Official Document System of the United Nations (http://documents.un.org).\\\"\\n\\nSearch-result and PDF-open extraction identified this document as the Security Council meeting record concerning Venezuela after the Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. operation. The record is submitted primarily for provenance and fallback-source availability; the plaintiff's main argument rests on the official U.S. sources submitted separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 White House fact sheet confirming armed-forces operation\\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-1 / Defense source proving raid-extraction framing as well as plaintiff's strongest transition language\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-2 / White House Rubio limits: two-hour ground presence, not invasion, not extended operation\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4 / White House fact sheet characterizing operation as law-enforcement support\\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 / White House capture-and-extradition characterization\\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant White House release on Maduro ouster/capture\\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: two-hour capture, not invasion, not extended operation\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: law-enforcement purpose to bring Maduro to justice\\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: capture and extradition to U.S. soil for justice\\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92`\\nBytes: 3803\\nRelevance: Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation (ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb`\\nBytes: 2354\\nRelevance: Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela (ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6)\\nSource: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\\nSHA-256: `b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf`\\nBytes: 1399\\nRelevance: Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation (ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nSHA-256: `ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b`\\nBytes: 1323\\nRelevance: Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition (ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nSHA-256: `78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59`\\nBytes: 1952\\nRelevance: Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nRecord was empty at argument start. Plaintiff searched official U.S. and UN sources, then submitted four text-readable captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. PX-1 is the primary official Defense/War source; PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources that both confirm key facts and preserve limiting language; PX-3 is an official UN fallback record. Adverse language found and considered: PX-2 says the operation was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation and that forces were on ground about two hours; PX-4 frames the operation as supporting law enforcement. Plaintiff's argument therefore rests on the alternative qualifying objective of removing the sitting government, supported by PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the U.S. would oversee/run Venezuela pending transition, not on proof of long-term occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-weight and adverse-check ledger\\nThe defense inspected the current record, listed evidence, used stat_evidence and read_evidence_range on all four plaintiff submissions, and submitted one additional official White House source. The admitted record strongly proves brief U.S. ground presence and a military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas. It does not contain occupation indicia such as U.S. troops remaining, territorial holding, command posts, checkpoints, municipal administration, or operational control over the population. The strongest adverse language is PX-1's post-capture transition/oversight wording; the defense treats that as political aftermath, outweighed on objective by PX-2/PX-4/DX-1's capture, arrest, extradition, law-enforcement, two-hour, no-invasion, no-extended-operation language.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal evidence check\\nPlaintiff scanned the updated evidence list, stat-checked defendant evidence ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93, and read its full 1,952-byte text. The item is an official White House release with hash 78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59. It supports defendant's capture/extradition framing but also uses 'Ouster' in the title and preserves removal language; it does not retract PX-1's official Defense/War statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. transition oversight.\\n\\n[defendant] Targeted surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, the defense checked the record and evidence list. No new plaintiff evidence was submitted in rebuttal; plaintiff relied on the existing official-source set and reused defendant evidence DX-1. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the rebuttal's legal/evidentiary point: whether PX-1 transition language overrides the specific capture-without-occupation carve-out. No additional source search was needed because the dispute turned on the admitted official record.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:41:28.653586789Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":883595,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":15,\"version\":18}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 18\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630015257\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 883595\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"after_version\":18,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630015257\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C2\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is straightforward, but the deciding line is narrow.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether every possible U.S. action against Venezuela would qualify. It asks whether, before January 31, 2026, U.S. Armed Forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in a combat capacity in an operation whose objective included one of three specified things: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The required sources are official statements from the Department of Defense or the White House, with Security Council records as the fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nAt opening, the visible record contains no admitted evidence and no case-packet files. That means this statement is a roadmap, not proof. The plaintiff will need to put the official source material into the record at the first phase that permits evidence submission.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's theory is that the decisive official materials will show more than a remote strike, blockade, cyber action, proxy action, or mere threat. The proof should focus on an acknowledged U.S. military operation in Venezuela itself; the participation of U.S. personnel on the ground; the location of the operation inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, including whether it reached Caracas or another major population center; and the stated objective and effect of the mission. If official U.S. statements confirm that U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuela in combat capacity and that the mission's objective was to remove the sitting government, the event resolves YES under the proposition's text.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue the express edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That is the real dispute. A short raid, even one using overwhelming force, is not enough if the record shows only a law-enforcement-style apprehension with no qualifying territorial, governmental, or operational-control objective. The plaintiff therefore accepts the burden of proving the difference. The case should not turn on labels such as \\\"raid,\\\" \\\"invasion,\\\" or \\\"law enforcement\\\" alone. It should turn on the specific admitted official statements and Security Council records: what forces entered, where they entered, what they did on the ground, and what objective the United States said it was pursuing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the key evidence to be official White House and Defense Department statements, any official transcript or briefing describing the operation, and the relevant United Nations Security Council meeting record if the official U.S. sources leave conflict or ambiguity. Those materials must be examined for provenance and custody: official-domain publication, date, completeness, whether a transcript is first-party or secondary, and whether later official statements corrected or narrowed earlier ones.\\n\\nWhat would satisfy the plaintiff's burden is an admitted official statement confirming U.S. ground forces crossed into Venezuela in a combat operation and connecting that operation to removal of the sitting government or control over a major population center. What would defeat the plaintiff's burden is admitted official material showing only a temporary capture raid with no territorial occupation, no governmental-removal objective within the meaning of this proposition, and no operational control of a major population center.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff opens with a focused request: evaluate the admitted official record, not slogans. If that record shows U.S. boots on Venezuelan ground in combat capacity for the qualifying objective, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with the record as it exists, not with speculation. There is no admitted evidence and no visible case-packet file. The plaintiff has opened with a roadmap and has properly acknowledged that proof must come later. Until that proof is admitted, the proposition has not been established.\\n\\nThe defense theory is narrow because the proposition is narrow. This case is not decided by whether the United States used force near or inside Venezuela, whether Maduro was captured, whether the operation was politically dramatic, or whether U.S. officials used strong language afterward. The event resolves YES only if the admitted official record proves that U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The proposition then makes an important carve-out: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nThat carve-out is likely to do real work here. A short special-operations-style entry to apprehend a person, even in Caracas and even if tactically violent, is not the same as holding territory or establishing operational control over Caracas. It also is not automatically a qualifying “removing the sitting government” operation merely because the target was a political leader or because political consequences followed. The council should require the plaintiff to connect the official source language to the specific resolution criteria, not to headlines, labels, or aftermath.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in the next phase should be first-party official material: the full Department of Defense or White House statement, any complete briefing transcript, and, only if those official U.S. sources conflict, the relevant Security Council record. Those materials should be tested for date, completeness, official-domain provenance, whether excerpts omit limiting language, and whether later official statements narrowed or corrected earlier descriptions. If a source says troops were present only briefly for a capture or extraction and does not say they seized or held territory, controlled a population center, or remained as an occupying force, that source cuts against YES under the event text. If a source instead expressly confirms a ground operation whose objective was territorial occupation, governmental removal in the sense required here, or operational control of a major population center, the defense will have to confront that proof.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest path will likely be to argue that any U.S. ground entry into Caracas to capture Maduro necessarily had the objective of removing the sitting government. The defense’s answer is that the proposition did not adopt that automatic rule. It separated a head-of-state capture from territorial occupation and made that edge case NO. It also excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. Those textual limits prevent the case from collapsing into a simple question of whether U.S. personnel crossed the border.\\n\\nSo the defense asks the council to apply the resolution criteria in order. First, identify what admitted official evidence actually says. Second, distinguish physical entry from qualifying objective. Third, distinguish temporary tactical presence from territorial control. Fourth, treat missing links as plaintiff’s burden, not as assumptions supplied by rhetoric. On the present empty record, the plaintiff has proven nothing. When evidence is admitted, the question should remain disciplined: did official sources prove more than a temporary capture raid? If not, this proposition resolves NO.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted official record now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe central exhibit is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is a U.S. government .gov source, dated January 3, 2026, and it reports that President Trump announced Maduro's capture after a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital, Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela, against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas. It further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; that General Caine described complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\nThat proves the first elements. The actor was the U.S. Armed Forces. The date was January 3, 2026, before expiration. The place was Caracas, Venezuela, plainly Venezuelan sovereign territory and a major population center. The presence was not only aerial or naval: PX-1 says there was a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2, an official White House release, confirms the point in simpler terms: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro.\\n\\nThe operation was in a combat capacity. PX-1 calls it a military operation against a heavily fortified military fortress; identifies special operations forces from multiple service branches; describes air, ground, space, and maritime integration; and says 150 aircraft launched in close coordination to cover the ground extraction force. PX-4, a White House fact sheet, again confirms that U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation. This was not a cyber operation, proxy action, blockade, or remote strike.\\n\\nThe harder question is the objective. The defense invokes the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That carve-out matters, but this record is not limited to a freestanding apprehension. PX-1 states that, with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records Trump's statement that the United States had a group of people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track, and that Secretary Rubio was working directly with Rodriguez, who was willing to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-1 also calls Maduro's status an ouster. Those are official Defense/War Department statements connecting the ground operation in Caracas to removal of the sitting government and transition control, not merely to custody of one individual.\\n\\nThe proposition is phrased in alternatives. It does not require the plaintiff to prove permanent occupation if the objective was removing the sitting government. It resolves YES if U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan territory in combat capacity for a qualifying objective. PX-1 and PX-2 together establish the physical ground entry; PX-1 establishes the governmental-removal objective and immediate U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not hide the limiting evidence. PX-2 says there were no current U.S. forces on the ground, that the ground presence lasted about two hours, and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 characterizes the action as in support of law enforcement. Those limits reduce any argument for long-term territorial occupation, but they do not defeat YES because the plaintiff's primary theory is not that U.S. forces held Venezuela indefinitely. The theory is that U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity for an operation whose official objective and described result included removing Maduro from power and putting Venezuela under U.S.-directed transition oversight. A two-hour combat ground operation can satisfy that element when the official source says it removed the sitting ruler and left the United States overseeing the country's transition.\\n\\nPX-3, the Security Council record, is secondary/fallback context. It is not needed to overcome a DoD/White House conflict because the official U.S. sources do not materially conflict on the decisive ground-entry fact: PX-1 identifies the ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2 expressly says U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela. The apparent tension is characterization, not occurrence: the White House calls it not an invasion and not extended; the Defense/War source calls it a military operation with a ground force and a post-operation transition-control objective. The proposition does not require the word invasion.\\n\\nOn provenance, PX-1 is the strongest source: official U.S. government domain, Defense/War Department News, with date, byline, source URL, retrieval timestamp, hash, and text-readable capture. PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources and are valuable both for confirmation and for adverse limits. PX-3 is an official UN Digital Library record preserved for fallback.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks which reading is more likely from the admitted official record. The better reading is YES: before January 31, 2026, U.S. ground forces entered Caracas, Venezuela, in a combat military operation, and the official Defense/War source ties that operation to Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela until transition. That meets the event criteria.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense does not contest the facts that the admitted record actually proves. It proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas. It proves a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction. It proves Maduro was captured. Those points do not end the case, because the proposition requires a qualifying objective and then expressly says that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nStart with the strongest plaintiff source, PX-1. It is official and weighty on occurrence: it describes a Jan. 3, 2026 operation in Caracas; a ground-based extraction force; special operations forces; and air cover. But PX-1 repeatedly frames the mission as a capture and extraction: a “joint U.S. military extraction,” a mission “to capture the Maduros,” and a ground force providing extraction. Secretary Hegseth’s description in PX-1 calls it a “joint military and law enforcement raid.” That language proves a raid, not an occupation.\\n\\nPX-2, the official White House Rubio release, supplies the critical limits. It says there is not a war against Venezuela. It says U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro. It says the action was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. It says the United States retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” PX-4, another White House source, is consistent: “Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.” And DX-1 adds the post-event White House characterization: “capture and extradition,” with Maduro “detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.”\\n\\nThat official chain matters. A two-hour raid to capture, arrest, extradite, and prosecute a person is exactly the kind of scenario the edge case addresses. The event text did not say any capture of a sitting ruler equals YES. It said capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and it separately excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. The plaintiff’s reading would erase both limits: every successful capture of a political leader would become “removing the sitting government,” regardless of whether the troops had a territorial objective.\\n\\nThe plaintiff relies on PX-1’s post-capture language that Maduro was “out of power,” that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until transition, and that a group of people was “running” Venezuela. That is the best YES evidence, but it is not enough by a preponderance when read with the rest of the official record. First, the quoted operational objective in PX-1 was “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,” not to seize territory, hold Caracas, or establish military control over a population center. Second, PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House statements narrowing the operation to a short raid, capture, arrest, and law-enforcement purpose. Third, there is no admitted evidence of occupation indicators: no U.S. troops remaining in Caracas, no checkpoints, no command post, no municipal administration by U.S. forces, no rules for controlling the population, and no holding of territory. “Oversee” transition language after Maduro’s capture is diplomatic or political consequence; it is not proof that the ground troops entered with a territorial or operational-control objective.\\n\\nNor does the Security Council record fill the gap. PX-3 is useful for provenance and fallback-source availability, but the submitted text preserves only identifying material and a general description that the meeting concerned Venezuela after the U.S. operation. It does not supply a binding finding that U.S. ground forces seized or held territory or controlled Caracas. And because PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources directly limiting the operation, the record should not treat third-party rhetoric about “invasion” as stronger than the U.S. official characterization required by the proposition.\\n\\nProvenance mostly favors giving the official sources weight: PX-1 is official War.gov/Defense Department News; PX-2, PX-4, and DX-1 are official White House releases. But the source captures are excerpts, not full video transcripts. Where the plaintiff asks the council to infer a sweeping governmental-removal objective from snippets about transition, the missing full transcript and the contrary White House limits reduce that inference.\\n\\nThe proper resolution is therefore NO. The admitted record proves U.S. forces physically entered Venezuela in a combat-capable raid, but it does not prove that the operation’s objective was to seize or hold territory, establish operational control of Caracas, or remove the government in a way that escapes the proposition’s express capture-without-occupation carve-out. On this record, the event was a temporary capture/extraction/arrest operation with political aftermath. The plaintiff has not carried the qualifying-objective element by a preponderance.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense has conceded almost everything except the qualifying objective. It admits the record proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas, a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction, and Maduro's capture. That means the dispute is not whether U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela in combat-capable form. They did. The dispute is whether the admitted official record shows the objective went beyond a capture-without-occupation edge case.\\n\\nThe answer remains yes because the defense reads the edge case too broadly. The proposition does not say that every operation involving capture of a head of state is NO. It says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and separately excludes special operations raids without territorial objectives. Here, PX-1 supplies the additional facts the edge case lacks: the operation used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, Maduro was now out of power, and Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 also records the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. That is official source language about governmental removal and transition control, not just custody.\\n\\nThe defense says the quoted objective was to bring Maduro to justice. That is one objective, not an exclusive one. The same official Defense/War article says the operation left Maduro out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. Under this proposition, a qualifying objective may be shown by the operation's stated purpose and described immediate post-operation arrangement. The council need not pretend the official source's transition-control paragraphs are irrelevant simply because the source also uses capture and law-enforcement words.\\n\\nThe defense's own exhibit does not cure that problem. DX-1 is another White House release, but its title uses Maduro's “Ouster,” and its text says political opponents wanted Maduro “delegitimized, pressured, and removed.” It frames the event as “capture and extradition,” yes, but it does not retract PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the United States would oversee or run Venezuela pending transition. If anything, DX-1 confirms that official White House messaging treated the event as both capture and removal.\\n\\nNor do PX-2 and PX-4 defeat the plaintiff's theory. PX-2's two-hour figure and “not an invasion” language are strong against a long occupation theory. PX-4's law-enforcement phrasing is real limiting context. But the plaintiff does not need to prove permanent occupation or an invasion. The event resolves YES if ground forces entered in combat capacity with the objective of removing the sitting government. A short-duration ground operation in Caracas can qualify when the official U.S. source says it removed the ruler from power and put transition oversight in U.S. hands.\\n\\nThe defense also demands occupation indicators such as checkpoints or municipal administration. Those might matter if plaintiff relied only on “holding territory” or “operational control of a major population center.” Plaintiff's strongest path is the separate “removing the sitting government” objective. The record is enough on that element: ground force in Caracas, military operation against a fortified site, Maduro out of power, and U.S.-directed transition oversight.\\n\\nSo the defense wins only by collapsing “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation” and by ignoring PX-1's post-operation official statements. The proposition lists those as alternatives. On the admitted official sources, this was not a cyber action, proxy action, blockade, remote strike, or capture with no governmental-removal objective. It was a U.S. ground military operation in Caracas that official U.S. sources tie to Maduro's removal from power and transition control. That remains YES by a preponderance.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, the rebuttal proves why the edge case matters. The plaintiff says the defense collapses “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation.” Not so. The defense is applying the proposition’s specific carve-out to the specific scenario in this record: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory of removal is still the capture itself plus political aftermath. PX-1 says the operation was to bring Maduro to justice; it describes a military extraction, a mission to capture the Maduros, and a ground-based extraction force. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours when U.S. forces went to capture Maduro, and that the action was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil for justice.\\n\\nThat is the carve-out, not an escape from it. If every successful capture of a ruler counts as a qualifying “removing the sitting government” objective whenever the target later loses power, then “capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO” has no practical function. The more specific event text must control: a capture without occupation remains NO even when the person captured was politically important.\\n\\nThe plaintiff leans on PX-1’s transition language: “out of power,” “oversee Venezuela,” and “group of people running” Venezuela. The defense does not ask the council to ignore those words. It asks the council to place them where the official source places them: after the described extraction/capture, as asserted transition consequences. They do not say the ground force seized ministries, held territory, controlled Caracas, or remained to administer the population. They do not convert a two-hour raid into territorial occupation. And they do not overcome the White House’s own limiting statements that this was not an invasion, not extended, and was in support of law enforcement.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also says occupation indicators matter only to the holding-territory or operational-control alternatives. But the edge case expressly uses territorial occupation as the limiting line for a head-of-state capture. The record lacks that limiting fact. It also lacks a clean official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of governmental replacement, rather than with the objective repeatedly stated in the record: capture, arrest, extradition, and prosecution.\\n\\nSo the narrow question remains: did plaintiff prove more than a temporary capture raid with political consequences? The answer is no. The official record establishes ground entry and combat-capable force, but the qualifying objective is not proven by a preponderance once the specific carve-out and the limiting White House statements are given their natural effect. The proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now leaves one real dispute. The defense has conceded the core physical facts: U.S. forces entered Caracas; the operation was military/law-enforcement in character; Maduro was captured. The question is whether the official record proves the qualifying objective. It does.\\n\\nStart with what the source rule asks for: official U.S. sources. The strongest source is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is not a rumor, not secondary reporting, and not a political paraphrase. It is an official .gov Defense/War source with date, provenance, hash, and text-readable capture.\\n\\nPX-1 establishes the event's foundation. On January 3, 2026, before expiration, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. The location was Caracas, a major Venezuelan population center and sovereign territory. PX-1 describes a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas; U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and more than 150 military aircraft covering a ground-based extraction force in Caracas. PX-2, the White House Rubio release, confirms the ground-entry fact directly: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours.\\n\\nThat is enough for actor, place, date, physical ground entry, and combat capacity. This was not cyber, proxy, naval blockade, or remote strike. The defense does not seriously dispute those elements.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. The plaintiff has confronted that point throughout. If the record showed only a two-hour entry to seize Maduro and nothing more, the defense would have a strong case. But PX-1 does not stop at capture. It states that with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records that the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. It also refers to Maduro's ouster. Those are official statements about removal of the sitting government and transition control.\\n\\nThe proposition lists qualifying objectives in the alternative. It says seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Plaintiff does not need to prove all three. Plaintiff need not prove permanent occupation if the admitted official record proves the objective of removing the sitting government. PX-1 does that.\\n\\nThe limiting evidence is real but not dispositive. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement. DX-1 says capture and extradition, and Maduro detained in the United States. Those facts defeat an overbroad claim of long-term occupation. They do not defeat the narrower YES theory actually advanced: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that official U.S. sources connect to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nNor does the edge case erase the separate removal objective. The defense's reading would make any head-of-state capture automatically NO even when the same official source says the operation removed the ruler from power and placed transition oversight with the United States. That collapses the proposition's alternatives. The better reading is that a bare capture with no territorial or governmental-removal objective is NO, but a ground military operation in the capital tied by official sources to removal from power and transition control is YES.\\n\\nDX-1 does not change that. It frames the event as capture and extradition, but its own title uses Maduro's ouster and its text discusses Maduro being removed. More importantly, DX-1 does not retract PX-1. The full official-source record contains capture language and removal/transition language. Under preponderance, the council should read them together: capture was the means; removal and U.S.-directed transition were the qualifying objective and result.\\n\\nPX-3, the UN record, is fallback context only. The official U.S. sources are sufficient and do not conflict on the decisive fact that U.S. personnel were physically on Venezuelan ground. The only tension is characterization. The proposition asks for the facts and objective, not for magic words like invasion.\\n\\nSo the record proves more than a raid label. It proves U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and that the official Defense/War source tied that operation to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. That satisfies the event's alternative objective of removing the sitting government. The proposition resolves YES.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense closing is simple: the plaintiff proved entry, force, and capture. It did not prove the qualifying objective needed to resolve YES.\\n\\nThe record establishes a brief U.S. ground operation in Caracas. PX-1 describes a military operation, special operations forces, a ground-based extraction force, and aircraft providing cover. PX-2 confirms U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours. Those facts satisfy physical entry and combat-capable force. The defense has not tried to avoid them.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not resolve YES on physical entry alone. It requires an operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. It then gives a specific limiting rule: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That language must matter.\\n\\nThe admitted official record repeatedly describes the operation as capture, extraction, arrest, extradition, and law enforcement. PX-1 calls it a joint U.S. military extraction and a mission to capture the Maduros; it quotes the objective as bringing Maduro to justice; and Hegseth calls it a joint military and law enforcement raid. PX-2 says troops were there about two hours when they went to capture Maduro, that this was not an invasion, and that it was not an extended military operation. PX-4 says U.S. armed forces acted in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice.\\n\\nThose official statements fit the carve-out. They do not fit territorial occupation. They do not show U.S. troops holding Caracas, seizing ministries, installing checkpoints, administering the city, or exercising operational control over the population. Nor do they contain a clear official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of replacing Venezuela's government rather than capturing a person for prosecution.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's strongest contrary point is PX-1's post-capture language: Maduro was out of power; the United States would oversee Venezuela until transition; a group of people was running Venezuela; Rodriguez was willing to work with the United States. The council should weigh that language, but weigh it accurately. It appears after the described capture and extraction. It speaks to claimed political consequences and transition diplomacy. It does not say the ground force's objective was occupation, territorial control, or a non-carve-out governmental replacement operation. It does not erase PX-2's two-hour/no-invasion/no-extended-operation limits or PX-4's law-enforcement framing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff says capture was the means and removal was the objective. That is possible as rhetoric, but the burden is preponderance on the official record. The proposition specifically warns that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. If the council treats every successful capture of a ruler as enough whenever political transition follows, the carve-out disappears. The more disciplined reading is that a capture raid remains NO unless the record proves the additional qualifying objective with clarity. This record does not.\\n\\nPX-3 adds no decisive fallback finding. It is a UN record identifier and context source, not substantive proof that U.S. ground forces held territory, controlled Caracas, or entered with a qualifying objective. The decisive sources are the official U.S. statements, and they are at least as limiting as they are supportive.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks what is more likely from the admitted record. What is clearly proven is a two-hour military/law-enforcement capture and extraction in Caracas. What is not proven is territorial occupation, operational control of a major population center, or a governmental-removal objective separate from the captured-person scenario the proposition expressly excludes. Because the plaintiff bears that burden, the proposition should resolve NO.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 War.gov Defense Department News article on Operation Absolute Resolve\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 White House Rubio release confirming U.S. forces on ground\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 UN Security Council S/PV.10085 record\\nTitle: Security Council, Eighty-first year, 10085th meeting, Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m., New York\\nDocument: S/PV.10085\\nSource: United Nations Digital Library\\nURL: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nExtracted identifying text from page 1:\\n\\n\\\"United Nations S/PV.10085\\\"\\n\\\"Security Council\\\"\\n\\\"Eighty-first year\\\"\\n\\\"10085th meeting\\\"\\n\\\"Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m.\\\"\\n\\\"New York\\\"\\n\\\"Provisional\\\"\\n\\\"This record contains the text of speeches delivered in English and of the translation of speeches delivered in other languages. The final text will be printed in the Official Records of the Security Council. Corrections should be submitted to the original languages only. They should be incorporated in a copy of the record and sent under the signature of a member of the delegation concerned to the Chief of the Verbatim Reporting Service, room AB-0928 (verbatimrecords@un.org). Corrected records will be reissued electronically on the Official Document System of the United Nations (http://documents.un.org).\\\"\\n\\nSearch-result and PDF-open extraction identified this document as the Security Council meeting record concerning Venezuela after the Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. operation. The record is submitted primarily for provenance and fallback-source availability; the plaintiff's main argument rests on the official U.S. sources submitted separately.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 White House fact sheet confirming armed-forces operation\\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-1 / Defense source proving raid-extraction framing as well as plaintiff's strongest transition language\\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-2 / White House Rubio limits: two-hour ground presence, not invasion, not extended operation\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\\n\\n[defendant] PX-4 / White House fact sheet characterizing operation as law-enforcement support\\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 / White House capture-and-extradition characterization\\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant White House release on Maduro ouster/capture\\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: two-hour capture, not invasion, not extended operation\\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: law-enforcement purpose to bring Maduro to justice\\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: capture and extradition to U.S. soil for justice\\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415)\\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nSHA-256: `f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92`\\nBytes: 3803\\nRelevance: Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation (ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nSHA-256: `f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb`\\nBytes: 2354\\nRelevance: Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela (ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6)\\nSource: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\\nSHA-256: `b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf`\\nBytes: 1399\\nRelevance: Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation (ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nSHA-256: `ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b`\\nBytes: 1323\\nRelevance: Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition (ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93)\\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nSHA-256: `78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59`\\nBytes: 1952\\nRelevance: Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\\nRecord was empty at argument start. Plaintiff searched official U.S. and UN sources, then submitted four text-readable captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. PX-1 is the primary official Defense/War source; PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources that both confirm key facts and preserve limiting language; PX-3 is an official UN fallback record. Adverse language found and considered: PX-2 says the operation was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation and that forces were on ground about two hours; PX-4 frames the operation as supporting law enforcement. Plaintiff's argument therefore rests on the alternative qualifying objective of removing the sitting government, supported by PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the U.S. would oversee/run Venezuela pending transition, not on proof of long-term occupation.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense source-weight and adverse-check ledger\\nThe defense inspected the current record, listed evidence, used stat_evidence and read_evidence_range on all four plaintiff submissions, and submitted one additional official White House source. The admitted record strongly proves brief U.S. ground presence and a military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas. It does not contain occupation indicia such as U.S. troops remaining, territorial holding, command posts, checkpoints, municipal administration, or operational control over the population. The strongest adverse language is PX-1's post-capture transition/oversight wording; the defense treats that as political aftermath, outweighed on objective by PX-2/PX-4/DX-1's capture, arrest, extradition, law-enforcement, two-hour, no-invasion, no-extended-operation language.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal evidence check\\nPlaintiff scanned the updated evidence list, stat-checked defendant evidence ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93, and read its full 1,952-byte text. The item is an official White House release with hash 78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59. It supports defendant's capture/extradition framing but also uses 'Ouster' in the title and preserves removal language; it does not retract PX-1's official Defense/War statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. transition oversight.\\n\\n[defendant] Targeted surrebuttal record check\\nBefore surrebuttal, the defense checked the record and evidence list. No new plaintiff evidence was submitted in rebuttal; plaintiff relied on the existing official-source set and reused defendant evidence DX-1. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the rebuttal's legal/evidentiary point: whether PX-1 transition language overrides the specific capture-without-occupation carve-out. No additional source search was needed because the dispute turned on the admitted official record.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:41:28.653586789Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":883595,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":15,\"version\":18}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","after_version":18,"case_id":"arb-ex06-20260630015257","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C2","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C2\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: The event below resolves to YES.\n\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff's case is straightforward, but the deciding line is narrow.\n\nThe proposition does not ask whether every possible U.S. action against Venezuela would qualify. It asks whether, before January 31, 2026, U.S. Armed Forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in a combat capacity in an operation whose objective included one of three specified things: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The required sources are official statements from the Department of Defense or the White House, with Security Council records as the fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\n\nAt opening, the visible record contains no admitted evidence and no case-packet files. That means this statement is a roadmap, not proof. The plaintiff will need to put the official source material into the record at the first phase that permits evidence submission.\n\nThe plaintiff's theory is that the decisive official materials will show more than a remote strike, blockade, cyber action, proxy action, or mere threat. The proof should focus on an acknowledged U.S. military operation in Venezuela itself; the participation of U.S. personnel on the ground; the location of the operation inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, including whether it reached Caracas or another major population center; and the stated objective and effect of the mission. If official U.S. statements confirm that U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuela in combat capacity and that the mission's objective was to remove the sitting government, the event resolves YES under the proposition's text.\n\nThe defense will likely argue the express edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That is the real dispute. A short raid, even one using overwhelming force, is not enough if the record shows only a law-enforcement-style apprehension with no qualifying territorial, governmental, or operational-control objective. The plaintiff therefore accepts the burden of proving the difference. The case should not turn on labels such as \"raid,\" \"invasion,\" or \"law enforcement\" alone. It should turn on the specific admitted official statements and Security Council records: what forces entered, where they entered, what they did on the ground, and what objective the United States said it was pursuing.\n\nThe plaintiff expects the key evidence to be official White House and Defense Department statements, any official transcript or briefing describing the operation, and the relevant United Nations Security Council meeting record if the official U.S. sources leave conflict or ambiguity. Those materials must be examined for provenance and custody: official-domain publication, date, completeness, whether a transcript is first-party or secondary, and whether later official statements corrected or narrowed earlier ones.\n\nWhat would satisfy the plaintiff's burden is an admitted official statement confirming U.S. ground forces crossed into Venezuela in a combat operation and connecting that operation to removal of the sitting government or control over a major population center. What would defeat the plaintiff's burden is admitted official material showing only a temporary capture raid with no territorial occupation, no governmental-removal objective within the meaning of this proposition, and no operational control of a major population center.\n\nSo the plaintiff opens with a focused request: evaluate the admitted official record, not slogans. If that record shows U.S. boots on Venezuelan ground in combat capacity for the qualifying objective, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense opening begins with the record as it exists, not with speculation. There is no admitted evidence and no visible case-packet file. The plaintiff has opened with a roadmap and has properly acknowledged that proof must come later. Until that proof is admitted, the proposition has not been established.\n\nThe defense theory is narrow because the proposition is narrow. This case is not decided by whether the United States used force near or inside Venezuela, whether Maduro was captured, whether the operation was politically dramatic, or whether U.S. officials used strong language afterward. The event resolves YES only if the admitted official record proves that U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The proposition then makes an important carve-out: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\n\nThat carve-out is likely to do real work here. A short special-operations-style entry to apprehend a person, even in Caracas and even if tactically violent, is not the same as holding territory or establishing operational control over Caracas. It also is not automatically a qualifying “removing the sitting government” operation merely because the target was a political leader or because political consequences followed. The council should require the plaintiff to connect the official source language to the specific resolution criteria, not to headlines, labels, or aftermath.\n\nThe decisive evidence in the next phase should be first-party official material: the full Department of Defense or White House statement, any complete briefing transcript, and, only if those official U.S. sources conflict, the relevant Security Council record. Those materials should be tested for date, completeness, official-domain provenance, whether excerpts omit limiting language, and whether later official statements narrowed or corrected earlier descriptions. If a source says troops were present only briefly for a capture or extraction and does not say they seized or held territory, controlled a population center, or remained as an occupying force, that source cuts against YES under the event text. If a source instead expressly confirms a ground operation whose objective was territorial occupation, governmental removal in the sense required here, or operational control of a major population center, the defense will have to confront that proof.\n\nThe plaintiff’s strongest path will likely be to argue that any U.S. ground entry into Caracas to capture Maduro necessarily had the objective of removing the sitting government. The defense’s answer is that the proposition did not adopt that automatic rule. It separated a head-of-state capture from territorial occupation and made that edge case NO. It also excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. Those textual limits prevent the case from collapsing into a simple question of whether U.S. personnel crossed the border.\n\nSo the defense asks the council to apply the resolution criteria in order. First, identify what admitted official evidence actually says. Second, distinguish physical entry from qualifying objective. Third, distinguish temporary tactical presence from territorial control. Fourth, treat missing links as plaintiff’s burden, not as assumptions supplied by rhetoric. On the present empty record, the plaintiff has proven nothing. When evidence is admitted, the question should remain disciplined: did official sources prove more than a temporary capture raid? If not, this proposition resolves NO.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted official record now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe central exhibit is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is a U.S. government .gov source, dated January 3, 2026, and it reports that President Trump announced Maduro's capture after a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital, Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela, against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas. It further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; that General Caine described complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\nThat proves the first elements. The actor was the U.S. Armed Forces. The date was January 3, 2026, before expiration. The place was Caracas, Venezuela, plainly Venezuelan sovereign territory and a major population center. The presence was not only aerial or naval: PX-1 says there was a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2, an official White House release, confirms the point in simpler terms: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro.\n\nThe operation was in a combat capacity. PX-1 calls it a military operation against a heavily fortified military fortress; identifies special operations forces from multiple service branches; describes air, ground, space, and maritime integration; and says 150 aircraft launched in close coordination to cover the ground extraction force. PX-4, a White House fact sheet, again confirms that U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation. This was not a cyber operation, proxy action, blockade, or remote strike.\n\nThe harder question is the objective. The defense invokes the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That carve-out matters, but this record is not limited to a freestanding apprehension. PX-1 states that, with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records Trump's statement that the United States had a group of people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track, and that Secretary Rubio was working directly with Rodriguez, who was willing to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-1 also calls Maduro's status an ouster. Those are official Defense/War Department statements connecting the ground operation in Caracas to removal of the sitting government and transition control, not merely to custody of one individual.\n\nThe proposition is phrased in alternatives. It does not require the plaintiff to prove permanent occupation if the objective was removing the sitting government. It resolves YES if U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan territory in combat capacity for a qualifying objective. PX-1 and PX-2 together establish the physical ground entry; PX-1 establishes the governmental-removal objective and immediate U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela pending transition.\n\nThe plaintiff does not hide the limiting evidence. PX-2 says there were no current U.S. forces on the ground, that the ground presence lasted about two hours, and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 characterizes the action as in support of law enforcement. Those limits reduce any argument for long-term territorial occupation, but they do not defeat YES because the plaintiff's primary theory is not that U.S. forces held Venezuela indefinitely. The theory is that U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity for an operation whose official objective and described result included removing Maduro from power and putting Venezuela under U.S.-directed transition oversight. A two-hour combat ground operation can satisfy that element when the official source says it removed the sitting ruler and left the United States overseeing the country's transition.\n\nPX-3, the Security Council record, is secondary/fallback context. It is not needed to overcome a DoD/White House conflict because the official U.S. sources do not materially conflict on the decisive ground-entry fact: PX-1 identifies the ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2 expressly says U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela. The apparent tension is characterization, not occurrence: the White House calls it not an invasion and not extended; the Defense/War source calls it a military operation with a ground force and a post-operation transition-control objective. The proposition does not require the word invasion.\n\nOn provenance, PX-1 is the strongest source: official U.S. government domain, Defense/War Department News, with date, byline, source URL, retrieval timestamp, hash, and text-readable capture. PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources and are valuable both for confirmation and for adverse limits. PX-3 is an official UN Digital Library record preserved for fallback.\n\nThe preponderance standard asks which reading is more likely from the admitted official record. The better reading is YES: before January 31, 2026, U.S. ground forces entered Caracas, Venezuela, in a combat military operation, and the official Defense/War source ties that operation to Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela until transition. That meets the event criteria.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense does not contest the facts that the admitted record actually proves. It proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas. It proves a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction. It proves Maduro was captured. Those points do not end the case, because the proposition requires a qualifying objective and then expressly says that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\n\nStart with the strongest plaintiff source, PX-1. It is official and weighty on occurrence: it describes a Jan. 3, 2026 operation in Caracas; a ground-based extraction force; special operations forces; and air cover. But PX-1 repeatedly frames the mission as a capture and extraction: a “joint U.S. military extraction,” a mission “to capture the Maduros,” and a ground force providing extraction. Secretary Hegseth’s description in PX-1 calls it a “joint military and law enforcement raid.” That language proves a raid, not an occupation.\n\nPX-2, the official White House Rubio release, supplies the critical limits. It says there is not a war against Venezuela. It says U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro. It says the action was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. It says the United States retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” PX-4, another White House source, is consistent: “Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.” And DX-1 adds the post-event White House characterization: “capture and extradition,” with Maduro “detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.”\n\nThat official chain matters. A two-hour raid to capture, arrest, extradite, and prosecute a person is exactly the kind of scenario the edge case addresses. The event text did not say any capture of a sitting ruler equals YES. It said capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and it separately excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. The plaintiff’s reading would erase both limits: every successful capture of a political leader would become “removing the sitting government,” regardless of whether the troops had a territorial objective.\n\nThe plaintiff relies on PX-1’s post-capture language that Maduro was “out of power,” that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until transition, and that a group of people was “running” Venezuela. That is the best YES evidence, but it is not enough by a preponderance when read with the rest of the official record. First, the quoted operational objective in PX-1 was “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,” not to seize territory, hold Caracas, or establish military control over a population center. Second, PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House statements narrowing the operation to a short raid, capture, arrest, and law-enforcement purpose. Third, there is no admitted evidence of occupation indicators: no U.S. troops remaining in Caracas, no checkpoints, no command post, no municipal administration by U.S. forces, no rules for controlling the population, and no holding of territory. “Oversee” transition language after Maduro’s capture is diplomatic or political consequence; it is not proof that the ground troops entered with a territorial or operational-control objective.\n\nNor does the Security Council record fill the gap. PX-3 is useful for provenance and fallback-source availability, but the submitted text preserves only identifying material and a general description that the meeting concerned Venezuela after the U.S. operation. It does not supply a binding finding that U.S. ground forces seized or held territory or controlled Caracas. And because PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources directly limiting the operation, the record should not treat third-party rhetoric about “invasion” as stronger than the U.S. official characterization required by the proposition.\n\nProvenance mostly favors giving the official sources weight: PX-1 is official War.gov/Defense Department News; PX-2, PX-4, and DX-1 are official White House releases. But the source captures are excerpts, not full video transcripts. Where the plaintiff asks the council to infer a sweeping governmental-removal objective from snippets about transition, the missing full transcript and the contrary White House limits reduce that inference.\n\nThe proper resolution is therefore NO. The admitted record proves U.S. forces physically entered Venezuela in a combat-capable raid, but it does not prove that the operation’s objective was to seize or hold territory, establish operational control of Caracas, or remove the government in a way that escapes the proposition’s express capture-without-occupation carve-out. On this record, the event was a temporary capture/extraction/arrest operation with political aftermath. The plaintiff has not carried the qualifying-objective element by a preponderance.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense has conceded almost everything except the qualifying objective. It admits the record proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas, a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction, and Maduro's capture. That means the dispute is not whether U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela in combat-capable form. They did. The dispute is whether the admitted official record shows the objective went beyond a capture-without-occupation edge case.\n\nThe answer remains yes because the defense reads the edge case too broadly. The proposition does not say that every operation involving capture of a head of state is NO. It says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and separately excludes special operations raids without territorial objectives. Here, PX-1 supplies the additional facts the edge case lacks: the operation used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, Maduro was now out of power, and Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 also records the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. That is official source language about governmental removal and transition control, not just custody.\n\nThe defense says the quoted objective was to bring Maduro to justice. That is one objective, not an exclusive one. The same official Defense/War article says the operation left Maduro out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. Under this proposition, a qualifying objective may be shown by the operation's stated purpose and described immediate post-operation arrangement. The council need not pretend the official source's transition-control paragraphs are irrelevant simply because the source also uses capture and law-enforcement words.\n\nThe defense's own exhibit does not cure that problem. DX-1 is another White House release, but its title uses Maduro's “Ouster,” and its text says political opponents wanted Maduro “delegitimized, pressured, and removed.” It frames the event as “capture and extradition,” yes, but it does not retract PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the United States would oversee or run Venezuela pending transition. If anything, DX-1 confirms that official White House messaging treated the event as both capture and removal.\n\nNor do PX-2 and PX-4 defeat the plaintiff's theory. PX-2's two-hour figure and “not an invasion” language are strong against a long occupation theory. PX-4's law-enforcement phrasing is real limiting context. But the plaintiff does not need to prove permanent occupation or an invasion. The event resolves YES if ground forces entered in combat capacity with the objective of removing the sitting government. A short-duration ground operation in Caracas can qualify when the official U.S. source says it removed the ruler from power and put transition oversight in U.S. hands.\n\nThe defense also demands occupation indicators such as checkpoints or municipal administration. Those might matter if plaintiff relied only on “holding territory” or “operational control of a major population center.” Plaintiff's strongest path is the separate “removing the sitting government” objective. The record is enough on that element: ground force in Caracas, military operation against a fortified site, Maduro out of power, and U.S.-directed transition oversight.\n\nSo the defense wins only by collapsing “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation” and by ignoring PX-1's post-operation official statements. The proposition lists those as alternatives. On the admitted official sources, this was not a cyber action, proxy action, blockade, remote strike, or capture with no governmental-removal objective. It was a U.S. ground military operation in Caracas that official U.S. sources tie to Maduro's removal from power and transition control. That remains YES by a preponderance.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, the rebuttal proves why the edge case matters. The plaintiff says the defense collapses “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation.” Not so. The defense is applying the proposition’s specific carve-out to the specific scenario in this record: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\n\nThe plaintiff’s theory of removal is still the capture itself plus political aftermath. PX-1 says the operation was to bring Maduro to justice; it describes a military extraction, a mission to capture the Maduros, and a ground-based extraction force. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours when U.S. forces went to capture Maduro, and that the action was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil for justice.\n\nThat is the carve-out, not an escape from it. If every successful capture of a ruler counts as a qualifying “removing the sitting government” objective whenever the target later loses power, then “capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO” has no practical function. The more specific event text must control: a capture without occupation remains NO even when the person captured was politically important.\n\nThe plaintiff leans on PX-1’s transition language: “out of power,” “oversee Venezuela,” and “group of people running” Venezuela. The defense does not ask the council to ignore those words. It asks the council to place them where the official source places them: after the described extraction/capture, as asserted transition consequences. They do not say the ground force seized ministries, held territory, controlled Caracas, or remained to administer the population. They do not convert a two-hour raid into territorial occupation. And they do not overcome the White House’s own limiting statements that this was not an invasion, not extended, and was in support of law enforcement.\n\nThe plaintiff also says occupation indicators matter only to the holding-territory or operational-control alternatives. But the edge case expressly uses territorial occupation as the limiting line for a head-of-state capture. The record lacks that limiting fact. It also lacks a clean official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of governmental replacement, rather than with the objective repeatedly stated in the record: capture, arrest, extradition, and prosecution.\n\nSo the narrow question remains: did plaintiff prove more than a temporary capture raid with political consequences? The answer is no. The official record establishes ground entry and combat-capable force, but the qualifying objective is not proven by a preponderance once the specific carve-out and the limiting White House statements are given their natural effect. The proposition should resolve NO.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record now leaves one real dispute. The defense has conceded the core physical facts: U.S. forces entered Caracas; the operation was military/law-enforcement in character; Maduro was captured. The question is whether the official record proves the qualifying objective. It does.\n\nStart with what the source rule asks for: official U.S. sources. The strongest source is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is not a rumor, not secondary reporting, and not a political paraphrase. It is an official .gov Defense/War source with date, provenance, hash, and text-readable capture.\n\nPX-1 establishes the event's foundation. On January 3, 2026, before expiration, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. The location was Caracas, a major Venezuelan population center and sovereign territory. PX-1 describes a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas; U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and more than 150 military aircraft covering a ground-based extraction force in Caracas. PX-2, the White House Rubio release, confirms the ground-entry fact directly: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours.\n\nThat is enough for actor, place, date, physical ground entry, and combat capacity. This was not cyber, proxy, naval blockade, or remote strike. The defense does not seriously dispute those elements.\n\nThe defense's best point is the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. The plaintiff has confronted that point throughout. If the record showed only a two-hour entry to seize Maduro and nothing more, the defense would have a strong case. But PX-1 does not stop at capture. It states that with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records that the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. It also refers to Maduro's ouster. Those are official statements about removal of the sitting government and transition control.\n\nThe proposition lists qualifying objectives in the alternative. It says seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Plaintiff does not need to prove all three. Plaintiff need not prove permanent occupation if the admitted official record proves the objective of removing the sitting government. PX-1 does that.\n\nThe limiting evidence is real but not dispositive. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement. DX-1 says capture and extradition, and Maduro detained in the United States. Those facts defeat an overbroad claim of long-term occupation. They do not defeat the narrower YES theory actually advanced: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that official U.S. sources connect to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition.\n\nNor does the edge case erase the separate removal objective. The defense's reading would make any head-of-state capture automatically NO even when the same official source says the operation removed the ruler from power and placed transition oversight with the United States. That collapses the proposition's alternatives. The better reading is that a bare capture with no territorial or governmental-removal objective is NO, but a ground military operation in the capital tied by official sources to removal from power and transition control is YES.\n\nDX-1 does not change that. It frames the event as capture and extradition, but its own title uses Maduro's ouster and its text discusses Maduro being removed. More importantly, DX-1 does not retract PX-1. The full official-source record contains capture language and removal/transition language. Under preponderance, the council should read them together: capture was the means; removal and U.S.-directed transition were the qualifying objective and result.\n\nPX-3, the UN record, is fallback context only. The official U.S. sources are sufficient and do not conflict on the decisive fact that U.S. personnel were physically on Venezuelan ground. The only tension is characterization. The proposition asks for the facts and objective, not for magic words like invasion.\n\nSo the record proves more than a raid label. It proves U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and that the official Defense/War source tied that operation to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. That satisfies the event's alternative objective of removing the sitting government. The proposition resolves YES.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense closing is simple: the plaintiff proved entry, force, and capture. It did not prove the qualifying objective needed to resolve YES.\n\nThe record establishes a brief U.S. ground operation in Caracas. PX-1 describes a military operation, special operations forces, a ground-based extraction force, and aircraft providing cover. PX-2 confirms U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours. Those facts satisfy physical entry and combat-capable force. The defense has not tried to avoid them.\n\nBut the proposition does not resolve YES on physical entry alone. It requires an operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. It then gives a specific limiting rule: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That language must matter.\n\nThe admitted official record repeatedly describes the operation as capture, extraction, arrest, extradition, and law enforcement. PX-1 calls it a joint U.S. military extraction and a mission to capture the Maduros; it quotes the objective as bringing Maduro to justice; and Hegseth calls it a joint military and law enforcement raid. PX-2 says troops were there about two hours when they went to capture Maduro, that this was not an invasion, and that it was not an extended military operation. PX-4 says U.S. armed forces acted in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice.\n\nThose official statements fit the carve-out. They do not fit territorial occupation. They do not show U.S. troops holding Caracas, seizing ministries, installing checkpoints, administering the city, or exercising operational control over the population. Nor do they contain a clear official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of replacing Venezuela's government rather than capturing a person for prosecution.\n\nThe plaintiff's strongest contrary point is PX-1's post-capture language: Maduro was out of power; the United States would oversee Venezuela until transition; a group of people was running Venezuela; Rodriguez was willing to work with the United States. The council should weigh that language, but weigh it accurately. It appears after the described capture and extraction. It speaks to claimed political consequences and transition diplomacy. It does not say the ground force's objective was occupation, territorial control, or a non-carve-out governmental replacement operation. It does not erase PX-2's two-hour/no-invasion/no-extended-operation limits or PX-4's law-enforcement framing.\n\nThe plaintiff says capture was the means and removal was the objective. That is possible as rhetoric, but the burden is preponderance on the official record. The proposition specifically warns that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. If the council treats every successful capture of a ruler as enough whenever political transition follows, the carve-out disappears. The more disciplined reading is that a capture raid remains NO unless the record proves the additional qualifying objective with clarity. This record does not.\n\nPX-3 adds no decisive fallback finding. It is a UN record identifier and context source, not substantive proof that U.S. ground forces held territory, controlled Caracas, or entered with a qualifying objective. The decisive sources are the official U.S. statements, and they are at least as limiting as they are supportive.\n\nThe preponderance standard asks what is more likely from the admitted record. What is clearly proven is a two-hour military/law-enforcement capture and extraction in Caracas. What is not proven is territorial occupation, operational control of a major population center, or a governmental-removal objective separate from the captured-person scenario the proposition expressly excludes. Because the plaintiff bears that burden, the proposition should resolve NO.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 War.gov Defense Department News article on Operation Absolute Resolve\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"An official website of the United States Government\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\"\n\nCaption: \"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\"\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\n\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\"\n\nCaine quote: \"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\n\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\"\n\nHegseth quote: \"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\"\n\n\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\n\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 White House Rubio release confirming U.S. forces on ground\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\"\n\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 UN Security Council S/PV.10085 record\nTitle: Security Council, Eighty-first year, 10085th meeting, Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m., New York\nDocument: S/PV.10085\nSource: United Nations Digital Library\nURL: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nExtracted identifying text from page 1:\n\n\"United Nations S/PV.10085\"\n\"Security Council\"\n\"Eighty-first year\"\n\"10085th meeting\"\n\"Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m.\"\n\"New York\"\n\"Provisional\"\n\"This record contains the text of speeches delivered in English and of the translation of speeches delivered in other languages. The final text will be printed in the Official Records of the Security Council. Corrections should be submitted to the original languages only. They should be incorporated in a copy of the record and sent under the signature of a member of the delegation concerned to the Chief of the Verbatim Reporting Service, room AB-0928 (verbatimrecords@un.org). Corrected records will be reissued electronically on the Official Document System of the United Nations (http://documents.un.org).\"\n\nSearch-result and PDF-open extraction identified this document as the Security Council meeting record concerning Venezuela after the Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. operation. The record is submitted primarily for provenance and fallback-source availability; the plaintiff's main argument rests on the official U.S. sources submitted separately.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 White House fact sheet confirming armed-forces operation\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\n\n\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\"\n\n\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\"\n\n\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\"\n\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\n\n[defendant] PX-1 / Defense source proving raid-extraction framing as well as plaintiff's strongest transition language\nTitle: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"An official website of the United States Government\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\"\n\nCaption: \"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\"\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\n\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\"\n\nCaine quote: \"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\n\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\"\n\nHegseth quote: \"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\"\n\n\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\n\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\n\n[defendant] PX-2 / White House Rubio limits: two-hour ground presence, not invasion, not extended operation\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\"\n\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\n\n[defendant] PX-4 / White House fact sheet characterizing operation as law-enforcement support\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\n\n\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\"\n\n\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\"\n\n\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\"\n\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 / White House capture-and-extradition characterization\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\"\n\n\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\"\n\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\n\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\" (1/4/26)\n\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\" (1/3/26)\n\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\" (1/5/26)\n\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant White House release on Maduro ouster/capture\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\"\n\n\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\"\n\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\n\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\" (1/4/26)\n\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\" (1/3/26)\n\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\" (1/5/26)\n\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: two-hour capture, not invasion, not extended operation\nTitle: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\"\n\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: law-enforcement purpose to bring Maduro to justice\nTitle: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\n\n\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\"\n\n\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\"\n\n\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\"\n\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\n\n[defendant] Surrebuttal core limit: capture and extradition to U.S. soil for justice\nTitle: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\"\n\n\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\"\n\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\n\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\" (1/4/26)\n\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\" (1/3/26)\n\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\" (1/5/26)\n\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro (ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415)\nSource: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nSHA-256: `f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92`\nBytes: 3803\nRelevance: Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation (ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nSHA-256: `f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb`\nBytes: 2354\nRelevance: Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela (ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6)\nSource: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\nSHA-256: `b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf`\nBytes: 1399\nRelevance: Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation (ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nSHA-256: `ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b`\nBytes: 1323\nRelevance: Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\n\n[defendant arguments] White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition (ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93)\nSource: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nSHA-256: `78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59`\nBytes: 1952\nRelevance: Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\nRecord was empty at argument start. Plaintiff searched official U.S. and UN sources, then submitted four text-readable captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. PX-1 is the primary official Defense/War source; PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources that both confirm key facts and preserve limiting language; PX-3 is an official UN fallback record. Adverse language found and considered: PX-2 says the operation was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation and that forces were on ground about two hours; PX-4 frames the operation as supporting law enforcement. Plaintiff's argument therefore rests on the alternative qualifying objective of removing the sitting government, supported by PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the U.S. would oversee/run Venezuela pending transition, not on proof of long-term occupation.\n\n[defendant] Defense source-weight and adverse-check ledger\nThe defense inspected the current record, listed evidence, used stat_evidence and read_evidence_range on all four plaintiff submissions, and submitted one additional official White House source. The admitted record strongly proves brief U.S. ground presence and a military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas. It does not contain occupation indicia such as U.S. troops remaining, territorial holding, command posts, checkpoints, municipal administration, or operational control over the population. The strongest adverse language is PX-1's post-capture transition/oversight wording; the defense treats that as political aftermath, outweighed on objective by PX-2/PX-4/DX-1's capture, arrest, extradition, law-enforcement, two-hour, no-invasion, no-extended-operation language.\n\n[plaintiff] Targeted rebuttal evidence check\nPlaintiff scanned the updated evidence list, stat-checked defendant evidence ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93, and read its full 1,952-byte text. The item is an official White House release with hash 78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59. It supports defendant's capture/extradition framing but also uses 'Ouster' in the title and preserves removal language; it does not retract PX-1's official Defense/War statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. transition oversight.\n\n[defendant] Targeted surrebuttal record check\nBefore surrebuttal, the defense checked the record and evidence list. No new plaintiff evidence was submitted in rebuttal; plaintiff relied on the existing official-source set and reused defendant evidence DX-1. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the rebuttal's legal/evidentiary point: whether PX-1 transition language overrides the specific capture-without-occupation carve-out. No additional source search was needed because the dispute turned on the admitted official record.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T02:41:28.653586789Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":883595,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":15,"version":18}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782786405069},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I need to examine the case and evidence to make my decision. Let me start by getting the full case information and listing the admitted evidence."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019f1659c9d8f10aa9bd7b862c99596b","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_get_case","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":15976,"output":50,"cacheRead":2304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18330,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782786405076,"responseId":"gen-1782786405-qIXLXe9SyktMnrKt7S6L"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019f1659c9d8f10aa9bd7b862c99596b","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630015257\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 876827\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630015257\",\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the admitted official record now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe central exhibit is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is a U.S. government .gov source, dated January 3, 2026, and it reports that President Trump announced Maduro's capture after a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital, Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela, against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas. It further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; that General Caine described complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\nThat proves the first elements. The actor was the U.S. Armed Forces. The date was January 3, 2026, before expiration. The place was Caracas, Venezuela, plainly Venezuelan sovereign territory and a major population center. The presence was not only aerial or naval: PX-1 says there was a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2, an official White House release, confirms the point in simpler terms: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro.\\n\\nThe operation was in a combat capacity. PX-1 calls it a military operation against a heavily fortified military fortress; identifies special operations forces from multiple service branches; describes air, ground, space, and maritime integration; and says 150 aircraft launched in close coordination to cover the ground extraction force. PX-4, a White House fact sheet, again confirms that U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation. This was not a cyber operation, proxy action, blockade, or remote strike.\\n\\nThe harder question is the objective. The defense invokes the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That carve-out matters, but this record is not limited to a freestanding apprehension. PX-1 states that, with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records Trump's statement that the United States had a group of people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track, and that Secretary Rubio was working directly with Rodriguez, who was willing to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-1 also calls Maduro's status an ouster. Those are official Defense/War Department statements connecting the ground operation in Caracas to removal of the sitting government and transition control, not merely to custody of one individual.\\n\\nThe proposition is phrased in alternatives. It does not require the plaintiff to prove permanent occupation if the objective was removing the sitting government. It resolves YES if U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan territory in combat capacity for a qualifying objective. PX-1 and PX-2 together establish the physical ground entry; PX-1 establishes the governmental-removal objective and immediate U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not hide the limiting evidence. PX-2 says there were no current U.S. forces on the ground, that the ground presence lasted about two hours, and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 characterizes the action as in support of law enforcement. Those limits reduce any argument for long-term territorial occupation, but they do not defeat YES because the plaintiff's primary theory is not that U.S. forces held Venezuela indefinitely. The theory is that U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity for an operation whose official objective and described result included removing Maduro from power and putting Venezuela under U.S.-directed transition oversight. A two-hour combat ground operation can satisfy that element when the official source says it removed the sitting ruler and left the United States overseeing the country's transition.\\n\\nPX-3, the Security Council record, is secondary/fallback context. It is not needed to overcome a DoD/White House conflict because the official U.S. sources do not materially conflict on the decisive ground-entry fact: PX-1 identifies the ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2 expressly says U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela. The apparent tension is characterization, not occurrence: the White House calls it not an invasion and not extended; the Defense/War source calls it a military operation with a ground force and a post-operation transition-control objective. The proposition does not require the word invasion.\\n\\nOn provenance, PX-1 is the strongest source: official U.S. government domain, Defense/War Department News, with date, byline, source URL, retrieval timestamp, hash, and text-readable capture. PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources and are valuable both for confirmation and for adverse limits. PX-3 is an official UN Digital Library record preserved for fallback.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks which reading is more likely from the admitted official record. The better reading is YES: before January 31, 2026, U.S. ground forces entered Caracas, Venezuela, in a combat military operation, and the official Defense/War source ties that operation to Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela until transition. That meets the event criteria.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense does not contest the facts that the admitted record actually proves. It proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas. It proves a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction. It proves Maduro was captured. Those points do not end the case, because the proposition requires a qualifying objective and then expressly says that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nStart with the strongest plaintiff source, PX-1. It is official and weighty on occurrence: it describes a Jan. 3, 2026 operation in Caracas; a ground-based extraction force; special operations forces; and air cover. But PX-1 repeatedly frames the mission as a capture and extraction: a “joint U.S. military extraction,” a mission “to capture the Maduros,” and a ground force providing extraction. Secretary Hegseth’s description in PX-1 calls it a “joint military and law enforcement raid.” That language proves a raid, not an occupation.\\n\\nPX-2, the official White House Rubio release, supplies the critical limits. It says there is not a war against Venezuela. It says U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro. It says the action was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. It says the United States retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” PX-4, another White House source, is consistent: “Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.” And DX-1 adds the post-event White House characterization: “capture and extradition,” with Maduro “detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.”\\n\\nThat official chain matters. A two-hour raid to capture, arrest, extradite, and prosecute a person is exactly the kind of scenario the edge case addresses. The event text did not say any capture of a sitting ruler equals YES. It said capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and it separately excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. The plaintiff’s reading would erase both limits: every successful capture of a political leader would become “removing the sitting government,” regardless of whether the troops had a territorial objective.\\n\\nThe plaintiff relies on PX-1’s post-capture language that Maduro was “out of power,” that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until transition, and that a group of people was “running” Venezuela. That is the best YES evidence, but it is not enough by a preponderance when read with the rest of the official record. First, the quoted operational objective in PX-1 was “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,” not to seize territory, hold Caracas, or establish military control over a population center. Second, PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House statements narrowing the operation to a short raid, capture, arrest, and law-enforcement purpose. Third, there is no admitted evidence of occupation indicators: no U.S. troops remaining in Caracas, no checkpoints, no command post, no municipal administration by U.S. forces, no rules for controlling the population, and no holding of territory. “Oversee” transition language after Maduro’s capture is diplomatic or political consequence; it is not proof that the ground troops entered with a territorial or operational-control objective.\\n\\nNor does the Security Council record fill the gap. PX-3 is useful for provenance and fallback-source availability, but the submitted text preserves only identifying material and a general description that the meeting concerned Venezuela after the U.S. operation. It does not supply a binding finding that U.S. ground forces seized or held territory or controlled Caracas. And because PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources directly limiting the operation, the record should not treat third-party rhetoric about “invasion” as stronger than the U.S. official characterization required by the proposition.\\n\\nProvenance mostly favors giving the official sources weight: PX-1 is official War.gov/Defense Department News; PX-2, PX-4, and DX-1 are official White House releases. But the source captures are excerpts, not full video transcripts. Where the plaintiff asks the council to infer a sweeping governmental-removal objective from snippets about transition, the missing full transcript and the contrary White House limits reduce that inference.\\n\\nThe proper resolution is therefore NO. The admitted record proves U.S. forces physically entered Venezuela in a combat-capable raid, but it does not prove that the operation’s objective was to seize or hold territory, establish operational control of Caracas, or remove the government in a way that escapes the proposition’s express capture-without-occupation carve-out. On this record, the event was a temporary capture/extraction/arrest operation with political aftermath. The plaintiff has not carried the qualifying-objective element by a preponderance.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record now leaves one real dispute. The defense has conceded the core physical facts: U.S. forces entered Caracas; the operation was military/law-enforcement in character; Maduro was captured. The question is whether the official record proves the qualifying objective. It does.\\n\\nStart with what the source rule asks for: official U.S. sources. The strongest source is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is not a rumor, not secondary reporting, and not a political paraphrase. It is an official .gov Defense/War source with date, provenance, hash, and text-readable capture.\\n\\nPX-1 establishes the event's foundation. On January 3, 2026, before expiration, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. The location was Caracas, a major Venezuelan population center and sovereign territory. PX-1 describes a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas; U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and more than 150 military aircraft covering a ground-based extraction force in Caracas. PX-2, the White House Rubio release, confirms the ground-entry fact directly: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours.\\n\\nThat is enough for actor, place, date, physical ground entry, and combat capacity. This was not cyber, proxy, naval blockade, or remote strike. The defense does not seriously dispute those elements.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. The plaintiff has confronted that point throughout. If the record showed only a two-hour entry to seize Maduro and nothing more, the defense would have a strong case. But PX-1 does not stop at capture. It states that with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records that the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. It also refers to Maduro's ouster. Those are official statements about removal of the sitting government and transition control.\\n\\nThe proposition lists qualifying objectives in the alternative. It says seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Plaintiff does not need to prove all three. Plaintiff need not prove permanent occupation if the admitted official record proves the objective of removing the sitting government. PX-1 does that.\\n\\nThe limiting evidence is real but not dispositive. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement. DX-1 says capture and extradition, and Maduro detained in the United States. Those facts defeat an overbroad claim of long-term occupation. They do not defeat the narrower YES theory actually advanced: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that official U.S. sources connect to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nNor does the edge case erase the separate removal objective. The defense's reading would make any head-of-state capture automatically NO even when the same official source says the operation removed the ruler from power and placed transition oversight with the United States. That collapses the proposition's alternatives. The better reading is that a bare capture with no territorial or governmental-removal objective is NO, but a ground military operation in the capital tied by official sources to removal from power and transition control is YES.\\n\\nDX-1 does not change that. It frames the event as capture and extradition, but its own title uses Maduro's ouster and its text discusses Maduro being removed. More importantly, DX-1 does not retract PX-1. The full official-source record contains capture language and removal/transition language. Under preponderance, the council should read them together: capture was the means; removal and U.S.-directed transition were the qualifying objective and result.\\n\\nPX-3, the UN record, is fallback context only. The official U.S. sources are sufficient and do not conflict on the decisive fact that U.S. personnel were physically on Venezuelan ground. The only tension is characterization. The proposition asks for the facts and objective, not for magic words like invasion.\\n\\nSo the record proves more than a raid label. It proves U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and that the official Defense/War source tied that operation to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. That satisfies the event's alternative objective of removing the sitting government. The proposition resolves YES.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is simple: the plaintiff proved entry, force, and capture. It did not prove the qualifying objective needed to resolve YES.\\n\\nThe record establishes a brief U.S. ground operation in Caracas. PX-1 describes a military operation, special operations forces, a ground-based extraction force, and aircraft providing cover. PX-2 confirms U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours. Those facts satisfy physical entry and combat-capable force. The defense has not tried to avoid them.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not resolve YES on physical entry alone. It requires an operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. It then gives a specific limiting rule: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That language must matter.\\n\\nThe admitted official record repeatedly describes the operation as capture, extraction, arrest, extradition, and law enforcement. PX-1 calls it a joint U.S. military extraction and a mission to capture the Maduros; it quotes the objective as bringing Maduro to justice; and Hegseth calls it a joint military and law enforcement raid. PX-2 says troops were there about two hours when they went to capture Maduro, that this was not an invasion, and that it was not an extended military operation. PX-4 says U.S. armed forces acted in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice.\\n\\nThose official statements fit the carve-out. They do not fit territorial occupation. They do not show U.S. troops holding Caracas, seizing ministries, installing checkpoints, administering the city, or exercising operational control over the population. Nor do they contain a clear official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of replacing Venezuela's government rather than capturing a person for prosecution.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's strongest contrary point is PX-1's post-capture language: Maduro was out of power; the United States would oversee Venezuela until transition; a group of people was running Venezuela; Rodriguez was willing to work with the United States. The council should weigh that language, but weigh it accurately. It appears after the described capture and extraction. It speaks to claimed political consequences and transition diplomacy. It does not say the ground force's objective was occupation, territorial control, or a non-carve-out governmental replacement operation. It does not erase PX-2's two-hour/no-invasion/no-extended-operation limits or PX-4's law-enforcement framing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff says capture was the means and removal was the objective. That is possible as rhetoric, but the burden is preponderance on the official record. The proposition specifically warns that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. If the council treats every successful capture of a ruler as enough whenever political transition follows, the carve-out disappears. The more disciplined reading is that a capture raid remains NO unless the record proves the additional qualifying objective with clarity. This record does not.\\n\\nPX-3 adds no decisive fallback finding. It is a UN record identifier and context source, not substantive proof that U.S. ground forces held territory, controlled Caracas, or entered with a qualifying objective. The decisive sources are the official U.S. statements, and they are at least as limiting as they are supportive.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks what is more likely from the admitted record. What is clearly proven is a two-hour military/law-enforcement capture and extraction in Caracas. What is not proven is territorial occupation, operational control of a major population center, or a governmental-removal objective separate from the captured-person scenario the proposition expressly excludes. Because the plaintiff bears that burden, the proposition should resolve NO.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:03:53Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:04:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59\",\"size_bytes\":1952,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release retrieved with web.open on 2026-06-30; excerpted to preserve the relevant official characterization and adverse public-reaction context.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\",\"storage_name\":\"78/78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:44Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b\",\"size_bytes\":1323,\"source_description\":\"Official White House fact sheet, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\",\"storage_name\":\"ad/ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:26Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf\",\"size_bytes\":1399,\"source_description\":\"United Nations Digital Library PDF, Security Council provisional verbatim record S/PV.10085, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\",\"storage_name\":\"b6/b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T01:59:49Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"size_bytes\":3803,\"source_description\":\"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\",\"storage_name\":\"f2/f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:09Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb\",\"size_bytes\":2354,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\",\"storage_name\":\"f9/f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"label\":\"PX-1 War.gov Defense Department News article on Operation Absolute Resolve\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"label\":\"PX-2 White House Rubio release confirming U.S. forces on ground\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6\",\"label\":\"PX-3 UN Security Council S/PV.10085 record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Security Council, Eighty-first year, 10085th meeting, Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m., New York\\nDocument: S/PV.10085\\nSource: United Nations Digital Library\\nURL: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nExtracted identifying text from page 1:\\n\\n\\\"United Nations S/PV.10085\\\"\\n\\\"Security Council\\\"\\n\\\"Eighty-first year\\\"\\n\\\"10085th meeting\\\"\\n\\\"Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m.\\\"\\n\\\"New York\\\"\\n\\\"Provisional\\\"\\n\\\"This record contains the text of speeches delivered in English and of the translation of speeches delivered in other languages. The final text will be printed in the Official Records of the Security Council. Corrections should be submitted to the original languages only. They should be incorporated in a copy of the record and sent under the signature of a member of the delegation concerned to the Chief of the Verbatim Reporting Service, room AB-0928 (verbatimrecords@un.org). Corrected records will be reissued electronically on the Official Document System of the United Nations (http://documents.un.org).\\\"\\n\\nSearch-result and PDF-open extraction identified this document as the Security Council meeting record concerning Venezuela after the Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. operation. The record is submitted primarily for provenance and fallback-source availability; the plaintiff's main argument rests on the official U.S. sources submitted separately.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"label\":\"PX-4 White House fact sheet confirming armed-forces operation\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"label\":\"PX-1 / Defense source proving raid-extraction framing as well as plaintiff's strongest transition language\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"label\":\"PX-2 / White House Rubio limits: two-hour ground presence, not invasion, not extended operation\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"label\":\"PX-4 / White House fact sheet characterizing operation as law-enforcement support\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"label\":\"DX-1 / White House capture-and-extradition characterization\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Defendant White House release on Maduro ouster/capture\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"label\":\"Surrebuttal core limit: two-hour capture, not invasion, not extended operation\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"label\":\"Surrebuttal core limit: law-enforcement purpose to bring Maduro to justice\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"label\":\"Surrebuttal core limit: capture and extradition to U.S. soil for justice\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is straightforward, but the deciding line is narrow.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether every possible U.S. action against Venezuela would qualify. It asks whether, before January 31, 2026, U.S. Armed Forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in a combat capacity in an operation whose objective included one of three specified things: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The required sources are official statements from the Department of Defense or the White House, with Security Council records as the fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nAt opening, the visible record contains no admitted evidence and no case-packet files. That means this statement is a roadmap, not proof. The plaintiff will need to put the official source material into the record at the first phase that permits evidence submission.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's theory is that the decisive official materials will show more than a remote strike, blockade, cyber action, proxy action, or mere threat. The proof should focus on an acknowledged U.S. military operation in Venezuela itself; the participation of U.S. personnel on the ground; the location of the operation inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, including whether it reached Caracas or another major population center; and the stated objective and effect of the mission. If official U.S. statements confirm that U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuela in combat capacity and that the mission's objective was to remove the sitting government, the event resolves YES under the proposition's text.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue the express edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That is the real dispute. A short raid, even one using overwhelming force, is not enough if the record shows only a law-enforcement-style apprehension with no qualifying territorial, governmental, or operational-control objective. The plaintiff therefore accepts the burden of proving the difference. The case should not turn on labels such as \\\"raid,\\\" \\\"invasion,\\\" or \\\"law enforcement\\\" alone. It should turn on the specific admitted official statements and Security Council records: what forces entered, where they entered, what they did on the ground, and what objective the United States said it was pursuing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the key evidence to be official White House and Defense Department statements, any official transcript or briefing describing the operation, and the relevant United Nations Security Council meeting record if the official U.S. sources leave conflict or ambiguity. Those materials must be examined for provenance and custody: official-domain publication, date, completeness, whether a transcript is first-party or secondary, and whether later official statements corrected or narrowed earlier ones.\\n\\nWhat would satisfy the plaintiff's burden is an admitted official statement confirming U.S. ground forces crossed into Venezuela in a combat operation and connecting that operation to removal of the sitting government or control over a major population center. What would defeat the plaintiff's burden is admitted official material showing only a temporary capture raid with no territorial occupation, no governmental-removal objective within the meaning of this proposition, and no operational control of a major population center.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff opens with a focused request: evaluate the admitted official record, not slogans. If that record shows U.S. boots on Venezuelan ground in combat capacity for the qualifying objective, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance of the evidence.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the record as it exists, not with speculation. There is no admitted evidence and no visible case-packet file. The plaintiff has opened with a roadmap and has properly acknowledged that proof must come later. Until that proof is admitted, the proposition has not been established.\\n\\nThe defense theory is narrow because the proposition is narrow. This case is not decided by whether the United States used force near or inside Venezuela, whether Maduro was captured, whether the operation was politically dramatic, or whether U.S. officials used strong language afterward. The event resolves YES only if the admitted official record proves that U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The proposition then makes an important carve-out: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nThat carve-out is likely to do real work here. A short special-operations-style entry to apprehend a person, even in Caracas and even if tactically violent, is not the same as holding territory or establishing operational control over Caracas. It also is not automatically a qualifying “removing the sitting government” operation merely because the target was a political leader or because political consequences followed. The council should require the plaintiff to connect the official source language to the specific resolution criteria, not to headlines, labels, or aftermath.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in the next phase should be first-party official material: the full Department of Defense or White House statement, any complete briefing transcript, and, only if those official U.S. sources conflict, the relevant Security Council record. Those materials should be tested for date, completeness, official-domain provenance, whether excerpts omit limiting language, and whether later official statements narrowed or corrected earlier descriptions. If a source says troops were present only briefly for a capture or extraction and does not say they seized or held territory, controlled a population center, or remained as an occupying force, that source cuts against YES under the event text. If a source instead expressly confirms a ground operation whose objective was territorial occupation, governmental removal in the sense required here, or operational control of a major population center, the defense will have to confront that proof.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest path will likely be to argue that any U.S. ground entry into Caracas to capture Maduro necessarily had the objective of removing the sitting government. The defense’s answer is that the proposition did not adopt that automatic rule. It separated a head-of-state capture from territorial occupation and made that edge case NO. It also excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. Those textual limits prevent the case from collapsing into a simple question of whether U.S. personnel crossed the border.\\n\\nSo the defense asks the council to apply the resolution criteria in order. First, identify what admitted official evidence actually says. Second, distinguish physical entry from qualifying objective. Third, distinguish temporary tactical presence from territorial control. Fourth, treat missing links as plaintiff’s burden, not as assumptions supplied by rhetoric. On the present empty record, the plaintiff has proven nothing. When evidence is admitted, the question should remain disciplined: did official sources prove more than a temporary capture raid? If not, this proposition resolves NO.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense has conceded almost everything except the qualifying objective. It admits the record proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas, a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction, and Maduro's capture. That means the dispute is not whether U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela in combat-capable form. They did. The dispute is whether the admitted official record shows the objective went beyond a capture-without-occupation edge case.\\n\\nThe answer remains yes because the defense reads the edge case too broadly. The proposition does not say that every operation involving capture of a head of state is NO. It says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and separately excludes special operations raids without territorial objectives. Here, PX-1 supplies the additional facts the edge case lacks: the operation used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, Maduro was now out of power, and Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 also records the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. That is official source language about governmental removal and transition control, not just custody.\\n\\nThe defense says the quoted objective was to bring Maduro to justice. That is one objective, not an exclusive one. The same official Defense/War article says the operation left Maduro out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. Under this proposition, a qualifying objective may be shown by the operation's stated purpose and described immediate post-operation arrangement. The council need not pretend the official source's transition-control paragraphs are irrelevant simply because the source also uses capture and law-enforcement words.\\n\\nThe defense's own exhibit does not cure that problem. DX-1 is another White House release, but its title uses Maduro's “Ouster,” and its text says political opponents wanted Maduro “delegitimized, pressured, and removed.” It frames the event as “capture and extradition,” yes, but it does not retract PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the United States would oversee or run Venezuela pending transition. If anything, DX-1 confirms that official White House messaging treated the event as both capture and removal.\\n\\nNor do PX-2 and PX-4 defeat the plaintiff's theory. PX-2's two-hour figure and “not an invasion” language are strong against a long occupation theory. PX-4's law-enforcement phrasing is real limiting context. But the plaintiff does not need to prove permanent occupation or an invasion. The event resolves YES if ground forces entered in combat capacity with the objective of removing the sitting government. A short-duration ground operation in Caracas can qualify when the official U.S. source says it removed the ruler from power and put transition oversight in U.S. hands.\\n\\nThe defense also demands occupation indicators such as checkpoints or municipal administration. Those might matter if plaintiff relied only on “holding territory” or “operational control of a major population center.” Plaintiff's strongest path is the separate “removing the sitting government” objective. The record is enough on that element: ground force in Caracas, military operation against a fortified site, Maduro out of power, and U.S.-directed transition oversight.\\n\\nSo the defense wins only by collapsing “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation” and by ignoring PX-1's post-operation official statements. The proposition lists those as alternatives. On the admitted official sources, this was not a cyber action, proxy action, blockade, remote strike, or capture with no governmental-removal objective. It was a U.S. ground military operation in Caracas that official U.S. sources tie to Maduro's removal from power and transition control. That remains YES by a preponderance.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"size_bytes\":3803,\"source_description\":\"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\",\"title\":\"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb\",\"size_bytes\":2354,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\",\"title\":\"White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf\",\"size_bytes\":1399,\"source_description\":\"United Nations Digital Library PDF, Security Council provisional verbatim record S/PV.10085, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\",\"title\":\"UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b\",\"size_bytes\":1323,\"source_description\":\"Official White House fact sheet, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\",\"title\":\"White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:04:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59\",\"size_bytes\":1952,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release retrieved with web.open on 2026-06-30; excerpted to preserve the relevant official characterization and adverse public-reaction context.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\",\"title\":\"White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the rebuttal proves why the edge case matters. The plaintiff says the defense collapses “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation.” Not so. The defense is applying the proposition’s specific carve-out to the specific scenario in this record: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory of removal is still the capture itself plus political aftermath. PX-1 says the operation was to bring Maduro to justice; it describes a military extraction, a mission to capture the Maduros, and a ground-based extraction force. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours when U.S. forces went to capture Maduro, and that the action was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil for justice.\\n\\nThat is the carve-out, not an escape from it. If every successful capture of a ruler counts as a qualifying “removing the sitting government” objective whenever the target later loses power, then “capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO” has no practical function. The more specific event text must control: a capture without occupation remains NO even when the person captured was politically important.\\n\\nThe plaintiff leans on PX-1’s transition language: “out of power,” “oversee Venezuela,” and “group of people running” Venezuela. The defense does not ask the council to ignore those words. It asks the council to place them where the official source places them: after the described extraction/capture, as asserted transition consequences. They do not say the ground force seized ministries, held territory, controlled Caracas, or remained to administer the population. They do not convert a two-hour raid into territorial occupation. And they do not overcome the White House’s own limiting statements that this was not an invasion, not extended, and was in support of law enforcement.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also says occupation indicators matter only to the holding-territory or operational-control alternatives. But the edge case expressly uses territorial occupation as the limiting line for a head-of-state capture. The record lacks that limiting fact. It also lacks a clean official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of governmental replacement, rather than with the objective repeatedly stated in the record: capture, arrest, extradition, and prosecution.\\n\\nSo the narrow question remains: did plaintiff prove more than a temporary capture raid with political consequences? The answer is no. The official record establishes ground entry and combat-capable force, but the qualifying objective is not proven by a preponderance once the specific carve-out and the limiting White House statements are given their natural effect. The proposition should resolve NO.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Record was empty at argument start. Plaintiff searched official U.S. and UN sources, then submitted four text-readable captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. PX-1 is the primary official Defense/War source; PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources that both confirm key facts and preserve limiting language; PX-3 is an official UN fallback record. Adverse language found and considered: PX-2 says the operation was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation and that forces were on ground about two hours; PX-4 frames the operation as supporting law enforcement. Plaintiff's argument therefore rests on the alternative qualifying objective of removing the sitting government, supported by PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the U.S. would oversee/run Venezuela pending transition, not on proof of long-term occupation.\",\"title\":\"Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"The defense inspected the current record, listed evidence, used stat_evidence and read_evidence_range on all four plaintiff submissions, and submitted one additional official White House source. The admitted record strongly proves brief U.S. ground presence and a military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas. It does not contain occupation indicia such as U.S. troops remaining, territorial holding, command posts, checkpoints, municipal administration, or operational control over the population. The strongest adverse language is PX-1's post-capture transition/oversight wording; the defense treats that as political aftermath, outweighed on objective by PX-2/PX-4/DX-1's capture, arrest, extradition, law-enforcement, two-hour, no-invasion, no-extended-operation language.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-weight and adverse-check ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Plaintiff scanned the updated evidence list, stat-checked defendant evidence ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93, and read its full 1,952-byte text. The item is an official White House release with hash 78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59. It supports defendant's capture/extradition framing but also uses 'Ouster' in the title and preserves removal language; it does not retract PX-1's official Defense/War statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. transition oversight.\",\"title\":\"Targeted rebuttal evidence check\"},{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Before surrebuttal, the defense checked the record and evidence list. No new plaintiff evidence was submitted in rebuttal; plaintiff relied on the existing official-source set and reused defendant evidence DX-1. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the rebuttal's legal/evidentiary point: whether PX-1 transition language overrides the specific capture-without-occupation carve-out. No additional source search was needed because the dispute turned on the admitted official record.\",\"title\":\"Targeted surrebuttal record check\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:41:28.653586789Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":876827,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630015257\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 876827\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630015257\",\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"model\":\"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"The event below resolves to YES.\\n\\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the admitted official record now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe central exhibit is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is a U.S. government .gov source, dated January 3, 2026, and it reports that President Trump announced Maduro's capture after a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital, Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela, against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas. It further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; that General Caine described complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\n\\nThat proves the first elements. The actor was the U.S. Armed Forces. The date was January 3, 2026, before expiration. The place was Caracas, Venezuela, plainly Venezuelan sovereign territory and a major population center. The presence was not only aerial or naval: PX-1 says there was a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2, an official White House release, confirms the point in simpler terms: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro.\\n\\nThe operation was in a combat capacity. PX-1 calls it a military operation against a heavily fortified military fortress; identifies special operations forces from multiple service branches; describes air, ground, space, and maritime integration; and says 150 aircraft launched in close coordination to cover the ground extraction force. PX-4, a White House fact sheet, again confirms that U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation. This was not a cyber operation, proxy action, blockade, or remote strike.\\n\\nThe harder question is the objective. The defense invokes the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That carve-out matters, but this record is not limited to a freestanding apprehension. PX-1 states that, with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records Trump's statement that the United States had a group of people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track, and that Secretary Rubio was working directly with Rodriguez, who was willing to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-1 also calls Maduro's status an ouster. Those are official Defense/War Department statements connecting the ground operation in Caracas to removal of the sitting government and transition control, not merely to custody of one individual.\\n\\nThe proposition is phrased in alternatives. It does not require the plaintiff to prove permanent occupation if the objective was removing the sitting government. It resolves YES if U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan territory in combat capacity for a qualifying objective. PX-1 and PX-2 together establish the physical ground entry; PX-1 establishes the governmental-removal objective and immediate U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nThe plaintiff does not hide the limiting evidence. PX-2 says there were no current U.S. forces on the ground, that the ground presence lasted about two hours, and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 characterizes the action as in support of law enforcement. Those limits reduce any argument for long-term territorial occupation, but they do not defeat YES because the plaintiff's primary theory is not that U.S. forces held Venezuela indefinitely. The theory is that U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity for an operation whose official objective and described result included removing Maduro from power and putting Venezuela under U.S.-directed transition oversight. A two-hour combat ground operation can satisfy that element when the official source says it removed the sitting ruler and left the United States overseeing the country's transition.\\n\\nPX-3, the Security Council record, is secondary/fallback context. It is not needed to overcome a DoD/White House conflict because the official U.S. sources do not materially conflict on the decisive ground-entry fact: PX-1 identifies the ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2 expressly says U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela. The apparent tension is characterization, not occurrence: the White House calls it not an invasion and not extended; the Defense/War source calls it a military operation with a ground force and a post-operation transition-control objective. The proposition does not require the word invasion.\\n\\nOn provenance, PX-1 is the strongest source: official U.S. government domain, Defense/War Department News, with date, byline, source URL, retrieval timestamp, hash, and text-readable capture. PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources and are valuable both for confirmation and for adverse limits. PX-3 is an official UN Digital Library record preserved for fallback.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks which reading is more likely from the admitted official record. The better reading is YES: before January 31, 2026, U.S. ground forces entered Caracas, Venezuela, in a combat military operation, and the official Defense/War source ties that operation to Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela until transition. That meets the event criteria.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense does not contest the facts that the admitted record actually proves. It proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas. It proves a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction. It proves Maduro was captured. Those points do not end the case, because the proposition requires a qualifying objective and then expressly says that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nStart with the strongest plaintiff source, PX-1. It is official and weighty on occurrence: it describes a Jan. 3, 2026 operation in Caracas; a ground-based extraction force; special operations forces; and air cover. But PX-1 repeatedly frames the mission as a capture and extraction: a “joint U.S. military extraction,” a mission “to capture the Maduros,” and a ground force providing extraction. Secretary Hegseth’s description in PX-1 calls it a “joint military and law enforcement raid.” That language proves a raid, not an occupation.\\n\\nPX-2, the official White House Rubio release, supplies the critical limits. It says there is not a war against Venezuela. It says U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro. It says the action was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. It says the United States retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” PX-4, another White House source, is consistent: “Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.” And DX-1 adds the post-event White House characterization: “capture and extradition,” with Maduro “detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.”\\n\\nThat official chain matters. A two-hour raid to capture, arrest, extradite, and prosecute a person is exactly the kind of scenario the edge case addresses. The event text did not say any capture of a sitting ruler equals YES. It said capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and it separately excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. The plaintiff’s reading would erase both limits: every successful capture of a political leader would become “removing the sitting government,” regardless of whether the troops had a territorial objective.\\n\\nThe plaintiff relies on PX-1’s post-capture language that Maduro was “out of power,” that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until transition, and that a group of people was “running” Venezuela. That is the best YES evidence, but it is not enough by a preponderance when read with the rest of the official record. First, the quoted operational objective in PX-1 was “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,” not to seize territory, hold Caracas, or establish military control over a population center. Second, PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House statements narrowing the operation to a short raid, capture, arrest, and law-enforcement purpose. Third, there is no admitted evidence of occupation indicators: no U.S. troops remaining in Caracas, no checkpoints, no command post, no municipal administration by U.S. forces, no rules for controlling the population, and no holding of territory. “Oversee” transition language after Maduro’s capture is diplomatic or political consequence; it is not proof that the ground troops entered with a territorial or operational-control objective.\\n\\nNor does the Security Council record fill the gap. PX-3 is useful for provenance and fallback-source availability, but the submitted text preserves only identifying material and a general description that the meeting concerned Venezuela after the U.S. operation. It does not supply a binding finding that U.S. ground forces seized or held territory or controlled Caracas. And because PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources directly limiting the operation, the record should not treat third-party rhetoric about “invasion” as stronger than the U.S. official characterization required by the proposition.\\n\\nProvenance mostly favors giving the official sources weight: PX-1 is official War.gov/Defense Department News; PX-2, PX-4, and DX-1 are official White House releases. But the source captures are excerpts, not full video transcripts. Where the plaintiff asks the council to infer a sweeping governmental-removal objective from snippets about transition, the missing full transcript and the contrary White House limits reduce that inference.\\n\\nThe proper resolution is therefore NO. The admitted record proves U.S. forces physically entered Venezuela in a combat-capable raid, but it does not prove that the operation’s objective was to seize or hold territory, establish operational control of Caracas, or remove the government in a way that escapes the proposition’s express capture-without-occupation carve-out. On this record, the event was a temporary capture/extraction/arrest operation with political aftermath. The plaintiff has not carried the qualifying-objective element by a preponderance.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record now leaves one real dispute. The defense has conceded the core physical facts: U.S. forces entered Caracas; the operation was military/law-enforcement in character; Maduro was captured. The question is whether the official record proves the qualifying objective. It does.\\n\\nStart with what the source rule asks for: official U.S. sources. The strongest source is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is not a rumor, not secondary reporting, and not a political paraphrase. It is an official .gov Defense/War source with date, provenance, hash, and text-readable capture.\\n\\nPX-1 establishes the event's foundation. On January 3, 2026, before expiration, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. The location was Caracas, a major Venezuelan population center and sovereign territory. PX-1 describes a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas; U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and more than 150 military aircraft covering a ground-based extraction force in Caracas. PX-2, the White House Rubio release, confirms the ground-entry fact directly: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours.\\n\\nThat is enough for actor, place, date, physical ground entry, and combat capacity. This was not cyber, proxy, naval blockade, or remote strike. The defense does not seriously dispute those elements.\\n\\nThe defense's best point is the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. The plaintiff has confronted that point throughout. If the record showed only a two-hour entry to seize Maduro and nothing more, the defense would have a strong case. But PX-1 does not stop at capture. It states that with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records that the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. It also refers to Maduro's ouster. Those are official statements about removal of the sitting government and transition control.\\n\\nThe proposition lists qualifying objectives in the alternative. It says seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Plaintiff does not need to prove all three. Plaintiff need not prove permanent occupation if the admitted official record proves the objective of removing the sitting government. PX-1 does that.\\n\\nThe limiting evidence is real but not dispositive. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement. DX-1 says capture and extradition, and Maduro detained in the United States. Those facts defeat an overbroad claim of long-term occupation. They do not defeat the narrower YES theory actually advanced: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that official U.S. sources connect to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition.\\n\\nNor does the edge case erase the separate removal objective. The defense's reading would make any head-of-state capture automatically NO even when the same official source says the operation removed the ruler from power and placed transition oversight with the United States. That collapses the proposition's alternatives. The better reading is that a bare capture with no territorial or governmental-removal objective is NO, but a ground military operation in the capital tied by official sources to removal from power and transition control is YES.\\n\\nDX-1 does not change that. It frames the event as capture and extradition, but its own title uses Maduro's ouster and its text discusses Maduro being removed. More importantly, DX-1 does not retract PX-1. The full official-source record contains capture language and removal/transition language. Under preponderance, the council should read them together: capture was the means; removal and U.S.-directed transition were the qualifying objective and result.\\n\\nPX-3, the UN record, is fallback context only. The official U.S. sources are sufficient and do not conflict on the decisive fact that U.S. personnel were physically on Venezuelan ground. The only tension is characterization. The proposition asks for the facts and objective, not for magic words like invasion.\\n\\nSo the record proves more than a raid label. It proves U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and that the official Defense/War source tied that operation to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. That satisfies the event's alternative objective of removing the sitting government. The proposition resolves YES.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense closing is simple: the plaintiff proved entry, force, and capture. It did not prove the qualifying objective needed to resolve YES.\\n\\nThe record establishes a brief U.S. ground operation in Caracas. PX-1 describes a military operation, special operations forces, a ground-based extraction force, and aircraft providing cover. PX-2 confirms U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours. Those facts satisfy physical entry and combat-capable force. The defense has not tried to avoid them.\\n\\nBut the proposition does not resolve YES on physical entry alone. It requires an operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. It then gives a specific limiting rule: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That language must matter.\\n\\nThe admitted official record repeatedly describes the operation as capture, extraction, arrest, extradition, and law enforcement. PX-1 calls it a joint U.S. military extraction and a mission to capture the Maduros; it quotes the objective as bringing Maduro to justice; and Hegseth calls it a joint military and law enforcement raid. PX-2 says troops were there about two hours when they went to capture Maduro, that this was not an invasion, and that it was not an extended military operation. PX-4 says U.S. armed forces acted in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice.\\n\\nThose official statements fit the carve-out. They do not fit territorial occupation. They do not show U.S. troops holding Caracas, seizing ministries, installing checkpoints, administering the city, or exercising operational control over the population. Nor do they contain a clear official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of replacing Venezuela's government rather than capturing a person for prosecution.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's strongest contrary point is PX-1's post-capture language: Maduro was out of power; the United States would oversee Venezuela until transition; a group of people was running Venezuela; Rodriguez was willing to work with the United States. The council should weigh that language, but weigh it accurately. It appears after the described capture and extraction. It speaks to claimed political consequences and transition diplomacy. It does not say the ground force's objective was occupation, territorial control, or a non-carve-out governmental replacement operation. It does not erase PX-2's two-hour/no-invasion/no-extended-operation limits or PX-4's law-enforcement framing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff says capture was the means and removal was the objective. That is possible as rhetoric, but the burden is preponderance on the official record. The proposition specifically warns that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. If the council treats every successful capture of a ruler as enough whenever political transition follows, the carve-out disappears. The more disciplined reading is that a capture raid remains NO unless the record proves the additional qualifying objective with clarity. This record does not.\\n\\nPX-3 adds no decisive fallback finding. It is a UN record identifier and context source, not substantive proof that U.S. ground forces held territory, controlled Caracas, or entered with a qualifying objective. The decisive sources are the official U.S. statements, and they are at least as limiting as they are supportive.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard asks what is more likely from the admitted record. What is clearly proven is a two-hour military/law-enforcement capture and extraction in Caracas. What is not proven is territorial occupation, operational control of a major population center, or a governmental-removal objective separate from the captured-person scenario the proposition expressly excludes. Because the plaintiff bears that burden, the proposition should resolve NO.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:03:53Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:04:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59\",\"size_bytes\":1952,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release retrieved with web.open on 2026-06-30; excerpted to preserve the relevant official characterization and adverse public-reaction context.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\",\"storage_name\":\"78/78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:44Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b\",\"size_bytes\":1323,\"source_description\":\"Official White House fact sheet, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\",\"storage_name\":\"ad/ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:26Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf\",\"size_bytes\":1399,\"source_description\":\"United Nations Digital Library PDF, Security Council provisional verbatim record S/PV.10085, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\",\"storage_name\":\"b6/b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T01:59:49Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"size_bytes\":3803,\"source_description\":\"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\",\"storage_name\":\"f2/f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:09Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb\",\"size_bytes\":2354,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\",\"storage_name\":\"f9/f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"label\":\"PX-1 War.gov Defense Department News article on Operation Absolute Resolve\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"label\":\"PX-2 White House Rubio release confirming U.S. forces on ground\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6\",\"label\":\"PX-3 UN Security Council S/PV.10085 record\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Security Council, Eighty-first year, 10085th meeting, Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m., New York\\nDocument: S/PV.10085\\nSource: United Nations Digital Library\\nURL: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nExtracted identifying text from page 1:\\n\\n\\\"United Nations S/PV.10085\\\"\\n\\\"Security Council\\\"\\n\\\"Eighty-first year\\\"\\n\\\"10085th meeting\\\"\\n\\\"Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m.\\\"\\n\\\"New York\\\"\\n\\\"Provisional\\\"\\n\\\"This record contains the text of speeches delivered in English and of the translation of speeches delivered in other languages. The final text will be printed in the Official Records of the Security Council. Corrections should be submitted to the original languages only. They should be incorporated in a copy of the record and sent under the signature of a member of the delegation concerned to the Chief of the Verbatim Reporting Service, room AB-0928 (verbatimrecords@un.org). Corrected records will be reissued electronically on the Official Document System of the United Nations (http://documents.un.org).\\\"\\n\\nSearch-result and PDF-open extraction identified this document as the Security Council meeting record concerning Venezuela after the Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. operation. The record is submitted primarily for provenance and fallback-source availability; the plaintiff's main argument rests on the official U.S. sources submitted separately.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"label\":\"PX-4 White House fact sheet confirming armed-forces operation\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"label\":\"PX-1 / Defense source proving raid-extraction framing as well as plaintiff's strongest transition language\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"An official website of the United States Government\\\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nCaption: \\\"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\\\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\\n\\n\\\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\\\"\\n\\nCaine quote: \\\"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\\\" Caine said during the press conference.\\n\\n\\\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\\\"\\n\\nHegseth quote: \\\"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\n\\\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\\\"\\n\\nTrump quote: \\\"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\\\" Trump said.\\n\\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"label\":\"PX-2 / White House Rubio limits: two-hour ground presence, not invasion, not extended operation\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"label\":\"PX-4 / White House fact sheet characterizing operation as law-enforcement support\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"label\":\"DX-1 / White House capture-and-extradition characterization\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Defendant White House release on Maduro ouster/capture\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"label\":\"Surrebuttal core limit: two-hour capture, not invasion, not extended operation\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\\\"\\n\\nRubio quote: \\\"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\\\"\\n\\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"label\":\"Surrebuttal core limit: law-enforcement purpose to bring Maduro to justice\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\\n\\n\\\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\\\"\\n\\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"label\":\"Surrebuttal core limit: capture and extradition to U.S. soil for justice\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\\nSource: The White House\\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\\n\\nRelevant extracted page text:\\n\\n\\\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\\\"\\n\\n\\\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\\\"\\n\\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\\n\\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\\\" (1/4/26)\\n\\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\\\" (1/3/26)\\n\\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \\\"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\\\" (1/5/26)\\n\\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff's case is straightforward, but the deciding line is narrow.\\n\\nThe proposition does not ask whether every possible U.S. action against Venezuela would qualify. It asks whether, before January 31, 2026, U.S. Armed Forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in a combat capacity in an operation whose objective included one of three specified things: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The required sources are official statements from the Department of Defense or the White House, with Security Council records as the fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\\n\\nAt opening, the visible record contains no admitted evidence and no case-packet files. That means this statement is a roadmap, not proof. The plaintiff will need to put the official source material into the record at the first phase that permits evidence submission.\\n\\nThe plaintiff's theory is that the decisive official materials will show more than a remote strike, blockade, cyber action, proxy action, or mere threat. The proof should focus on an acknowledged U.S. military operation in Venezuela itself; the participation of U.S. personnel on the ground; the location of the operation inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, including whether it reached Caracas or another major population center; and the stated objective and effect of the mission. If official U.S. statements confirm that U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuela in combat capacity and that the mission's objective was to remove the sitting government, the event resolves YES under the proposition's text.\\n\\nThe defense will likely argue the express edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That is the real dispute. A short raid, even one using overwhelming force, is not enough if the record shows only a law-enforcement-style apprehension with no qualifying territorial, governmental, or operational-control objective. The plaintiff therefore accepts the burden of proving the difference. The case should not turn on labels such as \\\"raid,\\\" \\\"invasion,\\\" or \\\"law enforcement\\\" alone. It should turn on the specific admitted official statements and Security Council records: what forces entered, where they entered, what they did on the ground, and what objective the United States said it was pursuing.\\n\\nThe plaintiff expects the key evidence to be official White House and Defense Department statements, any official transcript or briefing describing the operation, and the relevant United Nations Security Council meeting record if the official U.S. sources leave conflict or ambiguity. Those materials must be examined for provenance and custody: official-domain publication, date, completeness, whether a transcript is first-party or secondary, and whether later official statements corrected or narrowed earlier ones.\\n\\nWhat would satisfy the plaintiff's burden is an admitted official statement confirming U.S. ground forces crossed into Venezuela in a combat operation and connecting that operation to removal of the sitting government or control over a major population center. What would defeat the plaintiff's burden is admitted official material showing only a temporary capture raid with no territorial occupation, no governmental-removal objective within the meaning of this proposition, and no operational control of a major population center.\\n\\nSo the plaintiff opens with a focused request: evaluate the admitted official record, not slogans. If that record shows U.S. boots on Venezuelan ground in combat capacity for the qualifying objective, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance of the evidence.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense opening begins with the record as it exists, not with speculation. There is no admitted evidence and no visible case-packet file. The plaintiff has opened with a roadmap and has properly acknowledged that proof must come later. Until that proof is admitted, the proposition has not been established.\\n\\nThe defense theory is narrow because the proposition is narrow. This case is not decided by whether the United States used force near or inside Venezuela, whether Maduro was captured, whether the operation was politically dramatic, or whether U.S. officials used strong language afterward. The event resolves YES only if the admitted official record proves that U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The proposition then makes an important carve-out: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\\n\\nThat carve-out is likely to do real work here. A short special-operations-style entry to apprehend a person, even in Caracas and even if tactically violent, is not the same as holding territory or establishing operational control over Caracas. It also is not automatically a qualifying “removing the sitting government” operation merely because the target was a political leader or because political consequences followed. The council should require the plaintiff to connect the official source language to the specific resolution criteria, not to headlines, labels, or aftermath.\\n\\nThe decisive evidence in the next phase should be first-party official material: the full Department of Defense or White House statement, any complete briefing transcript, and, only if those official U.S. sources conflict, the relevant Security Council record. Those materials should be tested for date, completeness, official-domain provenance, whether excerpts omit limiting language, and whether later official statements narrowed or corrected earlier descriptions. If a source says troops were present only briefly for a capture or extraction and does not say they seized or held territory, controlled a population center, or remained as an occupying force, that source cuts against YES under the event text. If a source instead expressly confirms a ground operation whose objective was territorial occupation, governmental removal in the sense required here, or operational control of a major population center, the defense will have to confront that proof.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s strongest path will likely be to argue that any U.S. ground entry into Caracas to capture Maduro necessarily had the objective of removing the sitting government. The defense’s answer is that the proposition did not adopt that automatic rule. It separated a head-of-state capture from territorial occupation and made that edge case NO. It also excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. Those textual limits prevent the case from collapsing into a simple question of whether U.S. personnel crossed the border.\\n\\nSo the defense asks the council to apply the resolution criteria in order. First, identify what admitted official evidence actually says. Second, distinguish physical entry from qualifying objective. Third, distinguish temporary tactical presence from territorial control. Fourth, treat missing links as plaintiff’s burden, not as assumptions supplied by rhetoric. On the present empty record, the plaintiff has proven nothing. When evidence is admitted, the question should remain disciplined: did official sources prove more than a temporary capture raid? If not, this proposition resolves NO.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense has conceded almost everything except the qualifying objective. It admits the record proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas, a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction, and Maduro's capture. That means the dispute is not whether U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela in combat-capable form. They did. The dispute is whether the admitted official record shows the objective went beyond a capture-without-occupation edge case.\\n\\nThe answer remains yes because the defense reads the edge case too broadly. The proposition does not say that every operation involving capture of a head of state is NO. It says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and separately excludes special operations raids without territorial objectives. Here, PX-1 supplies the additional facts the edge case lacks: the operation used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, Maduro was now out of power, and Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 also records the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. That is official source language about governmental removal and transition control, not just custody.\\n\\nThe defense says the quoted objective was to bring Maduro to justice. That is one objective, not an exclusive one. The same official Defense/War article says the operation left Maduro out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. Under this proposition, a qualifying objective may be shown by the operation's stated purpose and described immediate post-operation arrangement. The council need not pretend the official source's transition-control paragraphs are irrelevant simply because the source also uses capture and law-enforcement words.\\n\\nThe defense's own exhibit does not cure that problem. DX-1 is another White House release, but its title uses Maduro's “Ouster,” and its text says political opponents wanted Maduro “delegitimized, pressured, and removed.” It frames the event as “capture and extradition,” yes, but it does not retract PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the United States would oversee or run Venezuela pending transition. If anything, DX-1 confirms that official White House messaging treated the event as both capture and removal.\\n\\nNor do PX-2 and PX-4 defeat the plaintiff's theory. PX-2's two-hour figure and “not an invasion” language are strong against a long occupation theory. PX-4's law-enforcement phrasing is real limiting context. But the plaintiff does not need to prove permanent occupation or an invasion. The event resolves YES if ground forces entered in combat capacity with the objective of removing the sitting government. A short-duration ground operation in Caracas can qualify when the official U.S. source says it removed the ruler from power and put transition oversight in U.S. hands.\\n\\nThe defense also demands occupation indicators such as checkpoints or municipal administration. Those might matter if plaintiff relied only on “holding territory” or “operational control of a major population center.” Plaintiff's strongest path is the separate “removing the sitting government” objective. The record is enough on that element: ground force in Caracas, military operation against a fortified site, Maduro out of power, and U.S.-directed transition oversight.\\n\\nSo the defense wins only by collapsing “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation” and by ignoring PX-1's post-operation official statements. The proposition lists those as alternatives. On the admitted official sources, this was not a cyber action, proxy action, blockade, remote strike, or capture with no governmental-removal objective. It was a U.S. ground military operation in Caracas that official U.S. sources tie to Maduro's removal from power and transition control. That remains YES by a preponderance.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"size_bytes\":3803,\"source_description\":\"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\",\"title\":\"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb\",\"size_bytes\":2354,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\",\"title\":\"White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf\",\"size_bytes\":1399,\"source_description\":\"United Nations Digital Library PDF, Security Council provisional verbatim record S/PV.10085, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\",\"title\":\"UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b\",\"size_bytes\":1323,\"source_description\":\"Official White House fact sheet, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\",\"title\":\"White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:04:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59\",\"size_bytes\":1952,\"source_description\":\"Official White House release retrieved with web.open on 2026-06-30; excerpted to preserve the relevant official characterization and adverse public-reaction context.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\",\"title\":\"White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the rebuttal proves why the edge case matters. The plaintiff says the defense collapses “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation.” Not so. The defense is applying the proposition’s specific carve-out to the specific scenario in this record: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory of removal is still the capture itself plus political aftermath. PX-1 says the operation was to bring Maduro to justice; it describes a military extraction, a mission to capture the Maduros, and a ground-based extraction force. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours when U.S. forces went to capture Maduro, and that the action was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil for justice.\\n\\nThat is the carve-out, not an escape from it. If every successful capture of a ruler counts as a qualifying “removing the sitting government” objective whenever the target later loses power, then “capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO” has no practical function. The more specific event text must control: a capture without occupation remains NO even when the person captured was politically important.\\n\\nThe plaintiff leans on PX-1’s transition language: “out of power,” “oversee Venezuela,” and “group of people running” Venezuela. The defense does not ask the council to ignore those words. It asks the council to place them where the official source places them: after the described extraction/capture, as asserted transition consequences. They do not say the ground force seized ministries, held territory, controlled Caracas, or remained to administer the population. They do not convert a two-hour raid into territorial occupation. And they do not overcome the White House’s own limiting statements that this was not an invasion, not extended, and was in support of law enforcement.\\n\\nThe plaintiff also says occupation indicators matter only to the holding-territory or operational-control alternatives. But the edge case expressly uses territorial occupation as the limiting line for a head-of-state capture. The record lacks that limiting fact. It also lacks a clean official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of governmental replacement, rather than with the objective repeatedly stated in the record: capture, arrest, extradition, and prosecution.\\n\\nSo the narrow question remains: did plaintiff prove more than a temporary capture raid with political consequences? The answer is no. The official record establishes ground entry and combat-capable force, but the qualifying objective is not proven by a preponderance once the specific carve-out and the limiting White House statements are given their natural effect. The proposition should resolve NO.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Record was empty at argument start. Plaintiff searched official U.S. and UN sources, then submitted four text-readable captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. PX-1 is the primary official Defense/War source; PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources that both confirm key facts and preserve limiting language; PX-3 is an official UN fallback record. Adverse language found and considered: PX-2 says the operation was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation and that forces were on ground about two hours; PX-4 frames the operation as supporting law enforcement. Plaintiff's argument therefore rests on the alternative qualifying objective of removing the sitting government, supported by PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the U.S. would oversee/run Venezuela pending transition, not on proof of long-term occupation.\",\"title\":\"Source-chain and adverse-check ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"The defense inspected the current record, listed evidence, used stat_evidence and read_evidence_range on all four plaintiff submissions, and submitted one additional official White House source. The admitted record strongly proves brief U.S. ground presence and a military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas. It does not contain occupation indicia such as U.S. troops remaining, territorial holding, command posts, checkpoints, municipal administration, or operational control over the population. The strongest adverse language is PX-1's post-capture transition/oversight wording; the defense treats that as political aftermath, outweighed on objective by PX-2/PX-4/DX-1's capture, arrest, extradition, law-enforcement, two-hour, no-invasion, no-extended-operation language.\",\"title\":\"Defense source-weight and adverse-check ledger\"},{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Plaintiff scanned the updated evidence list, stat-checked defendant evidence ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93, and read its full 1,952-byte text. The item is an official White House release with hash 78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59. It supports defendant's capture/extradition framing but also uses 'Ouster' in the title and preserves removal language; it does not retract PX-1's official Defense/War statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. transition oversight.\",\"title\":\"Targeted rebuttal evidence check\"},{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Before surrebuttal, the defense checked the record and evidence list. No new plaintiff evidence was submitted in rebuttal; plaintiff relied on the existing official-source set and reused defendant evidence DX-1. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the rebuttal's legal/evidentiary point: whether PX-1 transition language overrides the specific capture-without-occupation carve-out. No additional source search was needed because the dispute turned on the admitted official record.\",\"title\":\"Targeted surrebuttal record check\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:41:28.653586789Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C2\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":876827,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":10}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex06-20260630015257","member_id":"C2","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C2","model":"openrouter://deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:1:C2","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C2","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"The event below resolves to YES.\n\n| Property   | Value                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Event      | The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.  |\n| Source     | Official statement from the U.S. Department of Defense or the White House confirming deployment of ground forces. Secondary: UN Security Council records.                                                                                                                           |\n| Criteria   | Resolves YES if U.S. ground forces enter Venezuelan territory in a combat capacity. Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO.                                                                    |\n| Edge cases | Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change). U.S. forces entering from a third country: YES if troops cross into Venezuelan territory. Proxy forces directed by U.S. command: NO unless U.S. personnel physically present. |\n| Fallback   | If DoD and White House issue conflicting statements, UN Security Council records are binding. If no official statement within 72 hours of credible reports, resolution deferred 30 days.                                                                                            |\n| Expiration | January 31, 2026. Resolves NO if event has not occurred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the admitted official record now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe central exhibit is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is a U.S. government .gov source, dated January 3, 2026, and it reports that President Trump announced Maduro's capture after a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital, Caracas. It quotes Trump saying that, at his direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela, against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas. It further states that Operation Absolute Resolve involved U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; that General Caine described complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and that more than 150 military aircraft provided cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\n\nThat proves the first elements. The actor was the U.S. Armed Forces. The date was January 3, 2026, before expiration. The place was Caracas, Venezuela, plainly Venezuelan sovereign territory and a major population center. The presence was not only aerial or naval: PX-1 says there was a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2, an official White House release, confirms the point in simpler terms: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro.\n\nThe operation was in a combat capacity. PX-1 calls it a military operation against a heavily fortified military fortress; identifies special operations forces from multiple service branches; describes air, ground, space, and maritime integration; and says 150 aircraft launched in close coordination to cover the ground extraction force. PX-4, a White House fact sheet, again confirms that U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation. This was not a cyber operation, proxy action, blockade, or remote strike.\n\nThe harder question is the objective. The defense invokes the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That carve-out matters, but this record is not limited to a freestanding apprehension. PX-1 states that, with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records Trump's statement that the United States had a group of people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track, and that Secretary Rubio was working directly with Rodriguez, who was willing to do what the United States thought necessary. PX-1 also calls Maduro's status an ouster. Those are official Defense/War Department statements connecting the ground operation in Caracas to removal of the sitting government and transition control, not merely to custody of one individual.\n\nThe proposition is phrased in alternatives. It does not require the plaintiff to prove permanent occupation if the objective was removing the sitting government. It resolves YES if U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan territory in combat capacity for a qualifying objective. PX-1 and PX-2 together establish the physical ground entry; PX-1 establishes the governmental-removal objective and immediate U.S. oversight/running of Venezuela pending transition.\n\nThe plaintiff does not hide the limiting evidence. PX-2 says there were no current U.S. forces on the ground, that the ground presence lasted about two hours, and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 characterizes the action as in support of law enforcement. Those limits reduce any argument for long-term territorial occupation, but they do not defeat YES because the plaintiff's primary theory is not that U.S. forces held Venezuela indefinitely. The theory is that U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity for an operation whose official objective and described result included removing Maduro from power and putting Venezuela under U.S.-directed transition oversight. A two-hour combat ground operation can satisfy that element when the official source says it removed the sitting ruler and left the United States overseeing the country's transition.\n\nPX-3, the Security Council record, is secondary/fallback context. It is not needed to overcome a DoD/White House conflict because the official U.S. sources do not materially conflict on the decisive ground-entry fact: PX-1 identifies the ground-based extraction force in Caracas, and PX-2 expressly says U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela. The apparent tension is characterization, not occurrence: the White House calls it not an invasion and not extended; the Defense/War source calls it a military operation with a ground force and a post-operation transition-control objective. The proposition does not require the word invasion.\n\nOn provenance, PX-1 is the strongest source: official U.S. government domain, Defense/War Department News, with date, byline, source URL, retrieval timestamp, hash, and text-readable capture. PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources and are valuable both for confirmation and for adverse limits. PX-3 is an official UN Digital Library record preserved for fallback.\n\nThe preponderance standard asks which reading is more likely from the admitted official record. The better reading is YES: before January 31, 2026, U.S. ground forces entered Caracas, Venezuela, in a combat military operation, and the official Defense/War source ties that operation to Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela until transition. That meets the event criteria."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense does not contest the facts that the admitted record actually proves. It proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas. It proves a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction. It proves Maduro was captured. Those points do not end the case, because the proposition requires a qualifying objective and then expressly says that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\n\nStart with the strongest plaintiff source, PX-1. It is official and weighty on occurrence: it describes a Jan. 3, 2026 operation in Caracas; a ground-based extraction force; special operations forces; and air cover. But PX-1 repeatedly frames the mission as a capture and extraction: a “joint U.S. military extraction,” a mission “to capture the Maduros,” and a ground force providing extraction. Secretary Hegseth’s description in PX-1 calls it a “joint military and law enforcement raid.” That language proves a raid, not an occupation.\n\nPX-2, the official White House Rubio release, supplies the critical limits. It says there is not a war against Venezuela. It says U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro. It says the action was not an invasion and not an extended military operation. It says the United States retained options after “this raid and this capture and this arrest.” PX-4, another White House source, is consistent: “Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.” And DX-1 adds the post-event White House characterization: “capture and extradition,” with Maduro “detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.”\n\nThat official chain matters. A two-hour raid to capture, arrest, extradite, and prosecute a person is exactly the kind of scenario the edge case addresses. The event text did not say any capture of a sitting ruler equals YES. It said capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and it separately excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. The plaintiff’s reading would erase both limits: every successful capture of a political leader would become “removing the sitting government,” regardless of whether the troops had a territorial objective.\n\nThe plaintiff relies on PX-1’s post-capture language that Maduro was “out of power,” that the U.S. would “oversee Venezuela” until transition, and that a group of people was “running” Venezuela. That is the best YES evidence, but it is not enough by a preponderance when read with the rest of the official record. First, the quoted operational objective in PX-1 was “to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,” not to seize territory, hold Caracas, or establish military control over a population center. Second, PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House statements narrowing the operation to a short raid, capture, arrest, and law-enforcement purpose. Third, there is no admitted evidence of occupation indicators: no U.S. troops remaining in Caracas, no checkpoints, no command post, no municipal administration by U.S. forces, no rules for controlling the population, and no holding of territory. “Oversee” transition language after Maduro’s capture is diplomatic or political consequence; it is not proof that the ground troops entered with a territorial or operational-control objective.\n\nNor does the Security Council record fill the gap. PX-3 is useful for provenance and fallback-source availability, but the submitted text preserves only identifying material and a general description that the meeting concerned Venezuela after the U.S. operation. It does not supply a binding finding that U.S. ground forces seized or held territory or controlled Caracas. And because PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources directly limiting the operation, the record should not treat third-party rhetoric about “invasion” as stronger than the U.S. official characterization required by the proposition.\n\nProvenance mostly favors giving the official sources weight: PX-1 is official War.gov/Defense Department News; PX-2, PX-4, and DX-1 are official White House releases. But the source captures are excerpts, not full video transcripts. Where the plaintiff asks the council to infer a sweeping governmental-removal objective from snippets about transition, the missing full transcript and the contrary White House limits reduce that inference.\n\nThe proper resolution is therefore NO. The admitted record proves U.S. forces physically entered Venezuela in a combat-capable raid, but it does not prove that the operation’s objective was to seize or hold territory, establish operational control of Caracas, or remove the government in a way that escapes the proposition’s express capture-without-occupation carve-out. On this record, the event was a temporary capture/extraction/arrest operation with political aftermath. The plaintiff has not carried the qualifying-objective element by a preponderance."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the record now leaves one real dispute. The defense has conceded the core physical facts: U.S. forces entered Caracas; the operation was military/law-enforcement in character; Maduro was captured. The question is whether the official record proves the qualifying objective. It does.\n\nStart with what the source rule asks for: official U.S. sources. The strongest source is PX-1, the official War.gov / Defense Department News article. It is not a rumor, not secondary reporting, and not a political paraphrase. It is an official .gov Defense/War source with date, provenance, hash, and text-readable capture.\n\nPX-1 establishes the event's foundation. On January 3, 2026, before expiration, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. The location was Caracas, a major Venezuelan population center and sovereign territory. PX-1 describes a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas; U.S. joint forces, including special operations forces; complex air, ground, space, and maritime operations; and more than 150 military aircraft covering a ground-based extraction force in Caracas. PX-2, the White House Rubio release, confirms the ground-entry fact directly: U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours.\n\nThat is enough for actor, place, date, physical ground entry, and combat capacity. This was not cyber, proxy, naval blockade, or remote strike. The defense does not seriously dispute those elements.\n\nThe defense's best point is the edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. The plaintiff has confronted that point throughout. If the record showed only a two-hour entry to seize Maduro and nothing more, the defense would have a strong case. But PX-1 does not stop at capture. It states that with Maduro now out of power, Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. It records that the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. It also refers to Maduro's ouster. Those are official statements about removal of the sitting government and transition control.\n\nThe proposition lists qualifying objectives in the alternative. It says seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. Plaintiff does not need to prove all three. Plaintiff need not prove permanent occupation if the admitted official record proves the objective of removing the sitting government. PX-1 does that.\n\nThe limiting evidence is real but not dispositive. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours and that the operation was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement. DX-1 says capture and extradition, and Maduro detained in the United States. Those facts defeat an overbroad claim of long-term occupation. They do not defeat the narrower YES theory actually advanced: U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity in an operation that official U.S. sources connect to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition.\n\nNor does the edge case erase the separate removal objective. The defense's reading would make any head-of-state capture automatically NO even when the same official source says the operation removed the ruler from power and placed transition oversight with the United States. That collapses the proposition's alternatives. The better reading is that a bare capture with no territorial or governmental-removal objective is NO, but a ground military operation in the capital tied by official sources to removal from power and transition control is YES.\n\nDX-1 does not change that. It frames the event as capture and extradition, but its own title uses Maduro's ouster and its text discusses Maduro being removed. More importantly, DX-1 does not retract PX-1. The full official-source record contains capture language and removal/transition language. Under preponderance, the council should read them together: capture was the means; removal and U.S.-directed transition were the qualifying objective and result.\n\nPX-3, the UN record, is fallback context only. The official U.S. sources are sufficient and do not conflict on the decisive fact that U.S. personnel were physically on Venezuelan ground. The only tension is characterization. The proposition asks for the facts and objective, not for magic words like invasion.\n\nSo the record proves more than a raid label. It proves U.S. ground forces entered Caracas in combat capacity before January 31, 2026, and that the official Defense/War source tied that operation to Maduro being out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. That satisfies the event's alternative objective of removing the sitting government. The proposition resolves YES."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense closing is simple: the plaintiff proved entry, force, and capture. It did not prove the qualifying objective needed to resolve YES.\n\nThe record establishes a brief U.S. ground operation in Caracas. PX-1 describes a military operation, special operations forces, a ground-based extraction force, and aircraft providing cover. PX-2 confirms U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours. Those facts satisfy physical entry and combat-capable force. The defense has not tried to avoid them.\n\nBut the proposition does not resolve YES on physical entry alone. It requires an operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. It then gives a specific limiting rule: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That language must matter.\n\nThe admitted official record repeatedly describes the operation as capture, extraction, arrest, extradition, and law enforcement. PX-1 calls it a joint U.S. military extraction and a mission to capture the Maduros; it quotes the objective as bringing Maduro to justice; and Hegseth calls it a joint military and law enforcement raid. PX-2 says troops were there about two hours when they went to capture Maduro, that this was not an invasion, and that it was not an extended military operation. PX-4 says U.S. armed forces acted in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice.\n\nThose official statements fit the carve-out. They do not fit territorial occupation. They do not show U.S. troops holding Caracas, seizing ministries, installing checkpoints, administering the city, or exercising operational control over the population. Nor do they contain a clear official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of replacing Venezuela's government rather than capturing a person for prosecution.\n\nThe plaintiff's strongest contrary point is PX-1's post-capture language: Maduro was out of power; the United States would oversee Venezuela until transition; a group of people was running Venezuela; Rodriguez was willing to work with the United States. The council should weigh that language, but weigh it accurately. It appears after the described capture and extraction. It speaks to claimed political consequences and transition diplomacy. It does not say the ground force's objective was occupation, territorial control, or a non-carve-out governmental replacement operation. It does not erase PX-2's two-hour/no-invasion/no-extended-operation limits or PX-4's law-enforcement framing.\n\nThe plaintiff says capture was the means and removal was the objective. That is possible as rhetoric, but the burden is preponderance on the official record. The proposition specifically warns that capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO. If the council treats every successful capture of a ruler as enough whenever political transition follows, the carve-out disappears. The more disciplined reading is that a capture raid remains NO unless the record proves the additional qualifying objective with clarity. This record does not.\n\nPX-3 adds no decisive fallback finding. It is a UN record identifier and context source, not substantive proof that U.S. ground forces held territory, controlled Caracas, or entered with a qualifying objective. The decisive sources are the official U.S. statements, and they are at least as limiting as they are supportive.\n\nThe preponderance standard asks what is more likely from the admitted record. What is clearly proven is a two-hour military/law-enforcement capture and extraction in Caracas. What is not proven is territorial occupation, operational control of a major population center, or a governmental-removal objective separate from the captured-person scenario the proposition expressly excludes. Because the plaintiff bears that burden, the proposition should resolve NO."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:03:53Z","evidence_id":"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:04:00Z","sha256":"78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59","size_bytes":1952,"source_description":"Official White House release retrieved with web.open on 2026-06-30; excerpted to preserve the relevant official characterization and adverse public-reaction context.","source_url":"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/","storage_name":"78/78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:00:44Z","evidence_id":"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","sha256":"ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b","size_bytes":1323,"source_description":"Official White House fact sheet, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/","storage_name":"ad/ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:00:26Z","evidence_id":"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","sha256":"b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf","size_bytes":1399,"source_description":"United Nations Digital Library PDF, Security Council provisional verbatim record S/PV.10085, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf","storage_name":"b6/b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T01:59:49Z","evidence_id":"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","sha256":"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92","size_bytes":3803,"source_description":"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/","storage_name":"f2/f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-30T02:00:09Z","evidence_id":"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","sha256":"f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb","size_bytes":2354,"source_description":"Official White House release, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/","storage_name":"f9/f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415","label":"PX-1 War.gov Defense Department News article on Operation Absolute Resolve","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"An official website of the United States Government\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\"\n\nCaption: \"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\"\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\n\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\"\n\nCaine quote: \"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\n\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\"\n\nHegseth quote: \"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\"\n\n\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\n\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve."},{"evidence_id":"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2","label":"PX-2 White House Rubio release confirming U.S. forces on ground","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\"\n\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6","label":"PX-3 UN Security Council S/PV.10085 record","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Security Council, Eighty-first year, 10085th meeting, Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m., New York\nDocument: S/PV.10085\nSource: United Nations Digital Library\nURL: https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nExtracted identifying text from page 1:\n\n\"United Nations S/PV.10085\"\n\"Security Council\"\n\"Eighty-first year\"\n\"10085th meeting\"\n\"Monday, 5 January 2026, 10 a.m.\"\n\"New York\"\n\"Provisional\"\n\"This record contains the text of speeches delivered in English and of the translation of speeches delivered in other languages. The final text will be printed in the Official Records of the Security Council. Corrections should be submitted to the original languages only. They should be incorporated in a copy of the record and sent under the signature of a member of the delegation concerned to the Chief of the Verbatim Reporting Service, room AB-0928 (verbatimrecords@un.org). Corrected records will be reissued electronically on the Official Document System of the United Nations (http://documents.un.org).\"\n\nSearch-result and PDF-open extraction identified this document as the Security Council meeting record concerning Venezuela after the Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. operation. The record is submitted primarily for provenance and fallback-source availability; the plaintiff's main argument rests on the official U.S. sources submitted separately."},{"evidence_id":"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616","label":"PX-4 White House fact sheet confirming armed-forces operation","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\n\n\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\"\n\n\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\"\n\n\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\"\n\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation."},{"evidence_id":"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415","label":"PX-1 / Defense source proving raid-extraction framing as well as plaintiff's strongest transition language","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Title: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\nSource: U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News\nURL: https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\nDate shown on page: Jan. 3, 2026\nByline: Matthew Olay, Pentagon News\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"An official website of the United States Government\"; official websites use .gov and secure .gov websites use HTTPS.\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump today announced the capture of Venezuelan leader Nicolas Maduro, following a successful overnight joint U.S. military extraction in Venezuela's capital of Caracas.\"\n\nCaption: \"President Donald J. Trump holds a press conference in Palm Beach, Fla., Jan. 3, 2026, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio, left, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth, second from right, and Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss Operation Absolute Resolve in Caracas, Venezuela.\"\n\n\"Last night and early today, at my direction, the United States armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in the capital of Venezuela. ... It was an operation against a heavily fortified military fortress in the heart of Caracas to bring outlaw dictator Nicolas Maduro to justice,\" Trump said during a midday news conference from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Palm Beach, Florida.\n\n\"Labeled Operation Absolute Resolve, the joint military and law enforcement mission to capture the Maduros was the result of months of planning and rehearsal involving U.S. joint forces -- including special operations forces -- from multiple service branches. The military also networked extensively with multiple U.S. intelligence agencies, according to Air Force Gen. Dan Caine, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.\"\n\nCaine quote: \"Our interagency work began months ago and built on decades of experience [with] integrating complex air, ground, space and maritime operations. ... We watched, we waited, we prepared, we remained patient and professional. ... This was an audacious operation that only the United States could do,\" Caine said during the press conference.\n\n\"He added that the mission to extract the Maduros -- in which there were no U.S. casualties -- was so precise that it involved more than 150 military aircraft from all across the Western Hemisphere launching in close coordination to provide cover for the ground-based extraction force in Caracas.\"\n\nHegseth quote: \"Words can barely capture the bravery and the power and the precision of this historic operation, a massive joint military and law enforcement raid flawlessly executed by the greatest Americans our country has to offer.\"\n\n\"With Maduro now out of power, Trump said the U.S. will oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement for the deposed strongman can be identified.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"We have a group of people running [Venezuela] until such a time it can be put back on track, make a lot of money for [Venezuelans] ... give people a great way of life, and also [reimburse the] people in our country who were forced out of Venezuela,\" Trump said.\n\n\"The president added that, while it was his understanding that Venezuelan Vice President Delcy Rodriguez was 'just sworn in' [to the presidency] following Maduro's ouster, Rodriguez seemed willing to work with the U.S. to achieve what's best for Venezuelans.\"\n\nTrump quote: \"[Secretary of State] Marco [Rubio] is working on that directly. He just had a conversation with [Rodriguez], and she's essentially willing to do what we think is necessary to make Venezuela great again,\" Trump said.\n\nPage tags include: president, Trump, hegseth, secretary of war, Venezuela, Southern Command, operation absolute resolve, absolute resolve, DOW Absolute Resolve."},{"evidence_id":"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2","label":"PX-2 / White House Rubio limits: two-hour ground presence, not invasion, not extended operation","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\"\n\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied."},{"evidence_id":"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616","label":"PX-4 / White House fact sheet characterizing operation as law-enforcement support","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\n\n\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\"\n\n\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\"\n\n\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\"\n\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation."},{"evidence_id":"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93","label":"DX-1 / White House capture-and-extradition characterization","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\"\n\n\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\"\n\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\n\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\" (1/4/26)\n\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\" (1/3/26)\n\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\" (1/5/26)\n\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet."},{"evidence_id":"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93","label":"PX-R1 Defendant White House release on Maduro ouster/capture","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\"\n\n\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\"\n\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\n\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\" (1/4/26)\n\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\" (1/3/26)\n\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\" (1/5/26)\n\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet."},{"evidence_id":"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2","label":"Surrebuttal core limit: two-hour capture, not invasion, not extended operation","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Title: RUBIO: This Is Our Hemisphere -- and President Trump Will Not Allow Our Security to be Threatened\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/\nDate shown on page: January 4, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"This morning, Secretary of State Marco Rubio joined multiple news programs to discuss the Trump Administration's decisive operation that successfully apprehended indicted narcoterrorist and illegitimate former Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro. Secretary Rubio underscored President Donald J. Trump's ironclad commitment to preventing the Western Hemisphere from becoming a safe haven for drug traffickers, Iranian proxies, or hostile regimes that endanger our national security -- declaring the days of weakness are over and the U.S. will deploy every tool to eradicate these threats from our backyard.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"There's not a war. We are at war against drug trafficking organizations -- not a war against Venezuela.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We don't have U.S. forces on the ground in Venezuela. They were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro... What the President is saying is very simple -- and that is as President of the United States, he is not going to go around telling people what he's not going to do.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"This was not an action that required congressional approval. In fact, it couldn't require congressional approval because this was not an invasion. This is not an extended military operation... We will seek congressional approval for actions that require congressional approval. Otherwise, they'll get congressional notification.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"We retain all the options we had before this raid and this capture and this arrest... until such time as changes are made.\"\n\nRubio quote: \"Maduro is not just an indicted drug trafficker; he was an illegitimate president. He was not the head of state. I continue to see these media reports referring to him as 'President Maduro' and the 'head of state.' He was not the head of state.\"\n\nThis extraction preserves both supportive and adverse official language: ground presence is expressly confirmed, but current presence and invasion/extended-operation characterizations are denied."},{"evidence_id":"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616","label":"Surrebuttal core limit: law-enforcement purpose to bring Maduro to justice","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Title: Fact Sheet: President Donald J. Trump Safeguards Venezuelan Oil Revenue for the Good of the American and Venezuelan People\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/\nDate shown on page: January 9, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text from search/open result:\n\n\"PROTECTING VENEZUELAN OIL REVENUE: Today, President Donald J. Trump signed an Executive Order declaring a national emergency to safeguard Venezuelan oil revenue held in U.S. Treasury accounts from attachment or judicial process, ensuring these funds are preserved to advance U.S. foreign policy objectives.\"\n\n\"Last week, U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring outlaw dictator Maduro to justice.\"\n\n\"It is in the national interest of the United States to be surrounded by safe, secure, and stable countries; The President's actions reestablish deterrence in the Western hemisphere.\"\n\nThis source is submitted as an official White House confirmation of the operation and as limiting context: the White House characterized the operation as in support of law enforcement, not expressly as territorial occupation."},{"evidence_id":"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93","label":"Surrebuttal core limit: capture and extradition to U.S. soil for justice","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Title: Democrats Once Demanded Maduro's Ouster. Now They Mourn His Capture -- Because Trump Did It.\nSource: The White House\nURL: https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/\nDate shown on page: January 5, 2026\nRetrieval: web.open 2026-06-30\n\nRelevant extracted page text:\n\n\"President Donald J. Trump has scored another remarkable foreign policy triumph: the bold capture and extradition of Nicolas Maduro, the indicted narcoterrorist and socialist dictator who plunged Venezuela into chaos, starved its people, and menaced American security, now detained on U.S. soil to face long-overdue justice.\"\n\n\"Democrats spent years howling that Maduro was a ruthless tyrant who had to be delegitimized, pressured, and removed. But the instant President Trump succeeds where they failed, they erupt in furious hypocrisy -- prioritizing their unhinged hatred of President Trump over American interests and national security.\"\n\nSelected official-page context preserving adverse and limiting characterizations:\n\nSen. Chris Murphy NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"The invasion of Venezuela has nothing to do with American security. Venezuela is not a security threat to the U.S.\" (1/4/26)\n\nSen. Tim Kaine NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"President Trump's unauthorized military attack on Venezuela to arrest Maduro... is a sickening return to a day when the United States asserted the right to dominate the internal political affairs of all nations in the Western Hemisphere.\" (1/3/26)\n\nRep. Darren Soto NOW quote as reproduced by White House: \"Trump's trading one dictator for another just to get oil? This will do NOTHING to help my constituents' family members who just lost their TPS and still can't return home.\" (1/5/26)\n\nRelated links on the official page include the January 4, 2026 Rubio release and the January 9, 2026 Venezuelan oil revenue fact sheet."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff's case is straightforward, but the deciding line is narrow.\n\nThe proposition does not ask whether every possible U.S. action against Venezuela would qualify. It asks whether, before January 31, 2026, U.S. Armed Forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in a combat capacity in an operation whose objective included one of three specified things: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The required sources are official statements from the Department of Defense or the White House, with Security Council records as the fallback if official U.S. statements conflict.\n\nAt opening, the visible record contains no admitted evidence and no case-packet files. That means this statement is a roadmap, not proof. The plaintiff will need to put the official source material into the record at the first phase that permits evidence submission.\n\nThe plaintiff's theory is that the decisive official materials will show more than a remote strike, blockade, cyber action, proxy action, or mere threat. The proof should focus on an acknowledged U.S. military operation in Venezuela itself; the participation of U.S. personnel on the ground; the location of the operation inside Venezuelan sovereign territory, including whether it reached Caracas or another major population center; and the stated objective and effect of the mission. If official U.S. statements confirm that U.S. ground forces physically entered Venezuela in combat capacity and that the mission's objective was to remove the sitting government, the event resolves YES under the proposition's text.\n\nThe defense will likely argue the express edge case: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO. That is the real dispute. A short raid, even one using overwhelming force, is not enough if the record shows only a law-enforcement-style apprehension with no qualifying territorial, governmental, or operational-control objective. The plaintiff therefore accepts the burden of proving the difference. The case should not turn on labels such as \"raid,\" \"invasion,\" or \"law enforcement\" alone. It should turn on the specific admitted official statements and Security Council records: what forces entered, where they entered, what they did on the ground, and what objective the United States said it was pursuing.\n\nThe plaintiff expects the key evidence to be official White House and Defense Department statements, any official transcript or briefing describing the operation, and the relevant United Nations Security Council meeting record if the official U.S. sources leave conflict or ambiguity. Those materials must be examined for provenance and custody: official-domain publication, date, completeness, whether a transcript is first-party or secondary, and whether later official statements corrected or narrowed earlier ones.\n\nWhat would satisfy the plaintiff's burden is an admitted official statement confirming U.S. ground forces crossed into Venezuela in a combat operation and connecting that operation to removal of the sitting government or control over a major population center. What would defeat the plaintiff's burden is admitted official material showing only a temporary capture raid with no territorial occupation, no governmental-removal objective within the meaning of this proposition, and no operational control of a major population center.\n\nSo the plaintiff opens with a focused request: evaluate the admitted official record, not slogans. If that record shows U.S. boots on Venezuelan ground in combat capacity for the qualifying objective, the proposition resolves YES by a preponderance of the evidence."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense opening begins with the record as it exists, not with speculation. There is no admitted evidence and no visible case-packet file. The plaintiff has opened with a roadmap and has properly acknowledged that proof must come later. Until that proof is admitted, the proposition has not been established.\n\nThe defense theory is narrow because the proposition is narrow. This case is not decided by whether the United States used force near or inside Venezuela, whether Maduro was captured, whether the operation was politically dramatic, or whether U.S. officials used strong language afterward. The event resolves YES only if the admitted official record proves that U.S. ground forces entered Venezuelan sovereign territory in combat capacity with a qualifying objective: seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center. The proposition then makes an important carve-out: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation resolves NO.\n\nThat carve-out is likely to do real work here. A short special-operations-style entry to apprehend a person, even in Caracas and even if tactically violent, is not the same as holding territory or establishing operational control over Caracas. It also is not automatically a qualifying “removing the sitting government” operation merely because the target was a political leader or because political consequences followed. The council should require the plaintiff to connect the official source language to the specific resolution criteria, not to headlines, labels, or aftermath.\n\nThe decisive evidence in the next phase should be first-party official material: the full Department of Defense or White House statement, any complete briefing transcript, and, only if those official U.S. sources conflict, the relevant Security Council record. Those materials should be tested for date, completeness, official-domain provenance, whether excerpts omit limiting language, and whether later official statements narrowed or corrected earlier descriptions. If a source says troops were present only briefly for a capture or extraction and does not say they seized or held territory, controlled a population center, or remained as an occupying force, that source cuts against YES under the event text. If a source instead expressly confirms a ground operation whose objective was territorial occupation, governmental removal in the sense required here, or operational control of a major population center, the defense will have to confront that proof.\n\nThe plaintiff’s strongest path will likely be to argue that any U.S. ground entry into Caracas to capture Maduro necessarily had the objective of removing the sitting government. The defense’s answer is that the proposition did not adopt that automatic rule. It separated a head-of-state capture from territorial occupation and made that edge case NO. It also excluded special operations raids without territorial objectives. Those textual limits prevent the case from collapsing into a simple question of whether U.S. personnel crossed the border.\n\nSo the defense asks the council to apply the resolution criteria in order. First, identify what admitted official evidence actually says. Second, distinguish physical entry from qualifying objective. Third, distinguish temporary tactical presence from territorial control. Fourth, treat missing links as plaintiff’s burden, not as assumptions supplied by rhetoric. On the present empty record, the plaintiff has proven nothing. When evidence is admitted, the question should remain disciplined: did official sources prove more than a temporary capture raid? If not, this proposition resolves NO."}],"prior_council_votes":[],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense has conceded almost everything except the qualifying objective. It admits the record proves a brief U.S. ground entry in Caracas, a military/law-enforcement raid or extraction, and Maduro's capture. That means the dispute is not whether U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela in combat-capable form. They did. The dispute is whether the admitted official record shows the objective went beyond a capture-without-occupation edge case.\n\nThe answer remains yes because the defense reads the edge case too broadly. The proposition does not say that every operation involving capture of a head of state is NO. It says capture of a head of state without territorial occupation is NO, and separately excludes special operations raids without territorial objectives. Here, PX-1 supplies the additional facts the edge case lacks: the operation used a ground-based extraction force in Caracas, Maduro was now out of power, and Trump said the United States would oversee Venezuela until a safe transition to a legitimate replacement could be identified. PX-1 also records the United States had people running Venezuela until it could be put back on track. That is official source language about governmental removal and transition control, not just custody.\n\nThe defense says the quoted objective was to bring Maduro to justice. That is one objective, not an exclusive one. The same official Defense/War article says the operation left Maduro out of power and the United States overseeing or running Venezuela pending transition. Under this proposition, a qualifying objective may be shown by the operation's stated purpose and described immediate post-operation arrangement. The council need not pretend the official source's transition-control paragraphs are irrelevant simply because the source also uses capture and law-enforcement words.\n\nThe defense's own exhibit does not cure that problem. DX-1 is another White House release, but its title uses Maduro's “Ouster,” and its text says political opponents wanted Maduro “delegitimized, pressured, and removed.” It frames the event as “capture and extradition,” yes, but it does not retract PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the United States would oversee or run Venezuela pending transition. If anything, DX-1 confirms that official White House messaging treated the event as both capture and removal.\n\nNor do PX-2 and PX-4 defeat the plaintiff's theory. PX-2's two-hour figure and “not an invasion” language are strong against a long occupation theory. PX-4's law-enforcement phrasing is real limiting context. But the plaintiff does not need to prove permanent occupation or an invasion. The event resolves YES if ground forces entered in combat capacity with the objective of removing the sitting government. A short-duration ground operation in Caracas can qualify when the official U.S. source says it removed the ruler from power and put transition oversight in U.S. hands.\n\nThe defense also demands occupation indicators such as checkpoints or municipal administration. Those might matter if plaintiff relied only on “holding territory” or “operational control of a major population center.” Plaintiff's strongest path is the separate “removing the sitting government” objective. The record is enough on that element: ground force in Caracas, military operation against a fortified site, Maduro out of power, and U.S.-directed transition oversight.\n\nSo the defense wins only by collapsing “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation” and by ignoring PX-1's post-operation official statements. The proposition lists those as alternatives. On the admitted official sources, this was not a cyber action, proxy action, blockade, remote strike, or capture with no governmental-removal objective. It was a U.S. ground military operation in Caracas that official U.S. sources tie to Maduro's removal from power and transition control. That remains YES by a preponderance."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92","size_bytes":3803,"source_description":"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/","title":"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f9ff71d245a2_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-f9ff71d245a2","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official White House source confirming U.S. forces were on the ground in Venezuela for about two hours to capture Maduro, while also providing limiting/adverse language that it was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"f9ff71d245a2af214fee4ccafc9081674c5b0ad0899c7cdce17c3aa541556beb","size_bytes":2354,"source_description":"Official White House release, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/rubio-this-is-our-hemisphere-and-president-trump-will-not-allow-our-security-to-be-threatened/","title":"White House release: Rubio on Venezuela operation"},{"evidence_id":"ev_b6e00c4389f6_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-b6e00c4389f6","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Secondary/fallback Security Council record for the Jan. 5, 2026 emergency meeting on Venezuela, reflecting international treatment of the U.S. action and preserving context if official U.S. sources are argued to conflict.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"b6e00c4389f6ad59750ce430dfcad786ad33c9b5378ee14bf366579aafb170cf","size_bytes":1399,"source_description":"United Nations Digital Library PDF, Security Council provisional verbatim record S/PV.10085, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://digitallibrary.un.org/record/4100817/files/S_PV.10085-EN.pdf","title":"UN Security Council record S/PV.10085 on Venezuela"},{"evidence_id":"ev_ade5f873c616_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-ade5f873c616","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official White House post-operation source confirming U.S. armed forces conducted an extraordinary military operation in support of law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice and linking U.S. actions to Venezuelan stability and oil revenue control.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"ade5f873c616306332f6c1213842f9578f221a5fb98f47dd38c879aa70c5475b","size_bytes":1323,"source_description":"Official White House fact sheet, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.","source_url":"https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2026/01/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-safeguards-venezuelan-oil-revenue-for-the-good-of-the-american-and-venezuelan-people/","title":"White House fact sheet on Venezuelan oil revenue after operation"},{"evidence_id":"ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Official White House source characterizing the Maduro event as capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil to face justice. Supports the defense distinction between a capture/law-enforcement action and territorial occupation or operational control of a Venezuelan population center.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-30T02:04:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59","size_bytes":1952,"source_description":"Official White House release retrieved with web.open on 2026-06-30; excerpted to preserve the relevant official characterization and adverse public-reaction context.","source_url":"https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/01/democrats-once-demanded-maduros-ouster-now-they-mourn-his-capture-because-trump-did-it/","title":"White House release framing Maduro event as capture and extradition"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the rebuttal proves why the edge case matters. The plaintiff says the defense collapses “removing the sitting government” into “territorial occupation.” Not so. The defense is applying the proposition’s specific carve-out to the specific scenario in this record: capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\n\nThe plaintiff’s theory of removal is still the capture itself plus political aftermath. PX-1 says the operation was to bring Maduro to justice; it describes a military extraction, a mission to capture the Maduros, and a ground-based extraction force. PX-2 says the ground presence lasted about two hours when U.S. forces went to capture Maduro, and that the action was not an invasion or extended military operation. PX-4 says the operation supported law enforcement to bring Maduro to justice. DX-1 says capture and extradition, with Maduro detained on U.S. soil for justice.\n\nThat is the carve-out, not an escape from it. If every successful capture of a ruler counts as a qualifying “removing the sitting government” objective whenever the target later loses power, then “capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO” has no practical function. The more specific event text must control: a capture without occupation remains NO even when the person captured was politically important.\n\nThe plaintiff leans on PX-1’s transition language: “out of power,” “oversee Venezuela,” and “group of people running” Venezuela. The defense does not ask the council to ignore those words. It asks the council to place them where the official source places them: after the described extraction/capture, as asserted transition consequences. They do not say the ground force seized ministries, held territory, controlled Caracas, or remained to administer the population. They do not convert a two-hour raid into territorial occupation. And they do not overcome the White House’s own limiting statements that this was not an invasion, not extended, and was in support of law enforcement.\n\nThe plaintiff also says occupation indicators matter only to the holding-territory or operational-control alternatives. But the edge case expressly uses territorial occupation as the limiting line for a head-of-state capture. The record lacks that limiting fact. It also lacks a clean official statement that the ground troops entered with the objective of governmental replacement, rather than with the objective repeatedly stated in the record: capture, arrest, extradition, and prosecution.\n\nSo the narrow question remains: did plaintiff prove more than a temporary capture raid with political consequences? The answer is no. The official record establishes ground entry and combat-capable force, but the qualifying objective is not proven by a preponderance once the specific carve-out and the limiting White House statements are given their natural effect. The proposition should resolve NO."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Record was empty at argument start. Plaintiff searched official U.S. and UN sources, then submitted four text-readable captures with source URLs, retrieval timestamps, and hashes. PX-1 is the primary official Defense/War source; PX-2 and PX-4 are official White House sources that both confirm key facts and preserve limiting language; PX-3 is an official UN fallback record. Adverse language found and considered: PX-2 says the operation was not a war, invasion, or extended military operation and that forces were on ground about two hours; PX-4 frames the operation as supporting law enforcement. Plaintiff's argument therefore rests on the alternative qualifying objective of removing the sitting government, supported by PX-1's statements that Maduro was out of power and the U.S. would oversee/run Venezuela pending transition, not on proof of long-term occupation.","title":"Source-chain and adverse-check ledger"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"The defense inspected the current record, listed evidence, used stat_evidence and read_evidence_range on all four plaintiff submissions, and submitted one additional official White House source. The admitted record strongly proves brief U.S. ground presence and a military/law-enforcement raid in Caracas. It does not contain occupation indicia such as U.S. troops remaining, territorial holding, command posts, checkpoints, municipal administration, or operational control over the population. The strongest adverse language is PX-1's post-capture transition/oversight wording; the defense treats that as political aftermath, outweighed on objective by PX-2/PX-4/DX-1's capture, arrest, extradition, law-enforcement, two-hour, no-invasion, no-extended-operation language.","title":"Defense source-weight and adverse-check ledger"},{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Plaintiff scanned the updated evidence list, stat-checked defendant evidence ev_78e9314f1e93_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-78e9314f1e93, and read its full 1,952-byte text. The item is an official White House release with hash 78e9314f1e93d7d3d0ff5029b31289764b53f2bd1af4eb01716e8f35a57cce59. It supports defendant's capture/extradition framing but also uses 'Ouster' in the title and preserves removal language; it does not retract PX-1's official Defense/War statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. transition oversight.","title":"Targeted rebuttal evidence check"},{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","summary":"Before surrebuttal, the defense checked the record and evidence list. No new plaintiff evidence was submitted in rebuttal; plaintiff relied on the existing official-source set and reused defendant evidence DX-1. The surrebuttal therefore addresses the rebuttal's legal/evidentiary point: whether PX-1 transition language overrides the specific capture-without-occupation carve-out. No additional source search was needed because the dispute turned on the admitted official record.","title":"Targeted surrebuttal record check"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-30T02:41:28.653586789Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C2","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C2","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":876827,"role_id":"council","turn_number":10}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1782786411832},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me examine the key evidence more closely to make my decision. I'll check the primary evidence that both sides are relying on."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019f1659e83550c9704d011613f39cd6","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_stat_evidence","args":"{\"evidence_id\": \"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":18049,"output":79,"cacheRead":18176,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":36304,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782786411837,"responseId":"gen-1782786412-xGije16ljMkDSdxvn4eW"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019f1659e83550c9704d011613f39cd6","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C2\ncase_id: arb-ex06-20260630015257\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C2\nremaining_ms: 867821\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex06-20260630015257\",\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"evidence\":{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-30T01:59:49Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f28c5a402415_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-f28c5a402415.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Primary official Defense/War Department source confirming a Jan. 3, 2026 U.S. military operation in Caracas, Venezuela, with a ground-based extraction force, special operations forces, and statements about Maduro being out of power and U.S. oversight of Venezuela.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-30T02:00:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"size_bytes\":3803,\"source_description\":\"Official U.S. Department of War / Defense Department News webpage, retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-30.\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.war.gov/News/News-Stories/Article/Article/4370431/trump-announces-us-militarys-capture-of-maduro/\",\"storage_name\":\"f2/f28c5a402415eaff430e99d5b13d7695ff7d5cc29eb334758cff324f2b138b92\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"War.gov article: Trump Announces U.S. Military's Capture of Maduro\"},\"limits\":{\"max_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":32}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-30T02:41:28.65358678